SYMPTOM_TEXT: Narrative:  Symptoms:  Myalgia Treatment:

Patient reports that 2 hours after he received the Shingrix vaccination clinic he developed epigastric discomfort and felt dizzy as if he would faint. He then vomited and seemed to feel better. Because of the symptoms he presented to on Hospital emergency room and there was admitted for evaluation of syncope. Patient recalls that he underwent a CT scan of the brain which was okay, carotid duplex ultrasound studies which he reports was okay, was seen by Cardiologist and underwent a nuclear cardiac stress test which was abnormal. Under the direction of provider the patient was started on the above medications as indicated. He has been scheduled for a cardiac catheterization by provider for January 10, 2019 due to the abnormal findings on the nuclear cardiac stress test suspicious for angiographically significant coronary artery disease. Currently feels okay. Symptoms:  Dizziness, Headache & NauseaVomiting Treatment:  Metoprolol 12.5 mg BID ,Aspirin 81 mg every day ,Atorvastatin 20 mg every day
LAB_DATA: CT scan of brain: WNL Carotid duplex ultrasound: WNL Nuclear Cardiac stress test: Not WNL
HISTORY: Coronary artery disease, osteoarthritis, CODP, hyperlipidemia, actinic keratosis, nicotine dependence, senile hyperkeratosis

Husband arrived home from work @ 2:00 am and immediately to me to the ER.  Once admitted the Dr. stated that if a vaccine is injected incorrectly too high on the arm, (Which mine was very high).  The vaccine ends up entering the joint.  The antibodies in the vaccine have a reaction to your body that it's an infection.  They explained the IV meds they would be administering and doing shoulder xrays.  I was sent home with a sling, , anti-inflamatory ,medrol dose pak, cephalexin , oxycodone and Bactrim DS.  (for 7 Days) The first day, I did rest and sleep.  Taking the pain meds only the 1st day, but all others the entire 7 days, I was feeling much better and the pain was mild.  Now by 2 days after medication all gone.  I have consistent shoulder pain with arm movement.

vesicular rash above the right ear to the top of the head/ shingles; another vesicular rash on the right upper eyelid; Information has been received from a lawyer referring to a male patient of unknown age. Information about concurrent condition, history condition and concomitant medication was not reported. In or around 30-SEP-2014, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, route, lot# and expiration date unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered a vesicular rash above the right ear to the top of the head and another vesicular rash on the right upper eyelid (ophthalmic herpes zoster). The patient was diagnosed with shingles. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experiences mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was considered to be not recovered and causal relationship was assessed as related.    The lawyer considered the events shingles and ophthalmic herpes zoster to be disability.   Upon internal review, ophthalmic herpes zoster was determined to be medically significant.

After I received the first shingles shot my arm was a little sore. When I got home my arm was still sore around the injection site so I applied a warm compress. A few days after, the injection site started to feel hard to touch and warm. I spoke with the pharmacist and he said when they gave me the injection they must have administered the shot a little low. He also stated the pain would go away with time. I waited for a month for the pain to go away and it did not so contacted pharmacist again and he told me that he would contact the corporate office. A week later they contacted me and told me they would report the reaction. The pain is still constant when I move my arm. It feels like a painful cramp when I move my arm. The pain shoots down my arm to my hands. If i continue to move it the pain gets worse. I have to wait for the pain to stop before I can get any relief. i spoke to my primary care doctor and he stated there was nothing he could do and I would have to speak with the pharmacist again.
OTHER_MEDS: thyroid med, vertigo med, calcium, and Multi Vitamin

Follow up information has been received on 02-DEC-2020 from a lawyer via a Plaintiff Fact Sheet regarding a case in litigation referring to a 50-year-old male patient (pt). Pt did not smoke or use tobacco products. In 2012, he claimed for a disability and he granted it. On 29-SEP-2015, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) in his left arm at a pharmacy as prescribed by a physician. On the same date, he received concomitantly varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown). The pt claimed that he had suffered the following physical injuries caused by zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX): shingles (herpes zoster) and chickenpox. On approximately 01-OCT-2015 (also reported as three days after getting the vaccine), he first became aware of the injuries as he had blisters and scabs all over his body, had headaches and his whole body hurt and stinger, he also had fever. In October 2015, he was diagnosed with blisters, scabs, fever and pain by a physician who prescribed acyclovir. Pt did not know if a test was ever performed to determine if the rash was wild type or vaccine strain varicella zoster virus. No healthcare professional (HCP) told him he had vaccine strain varicella zoster virus. The pt claimed that receipt of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) caused or aggravated the following psychiatric and/or psychological condition for which treatment was sought from a HCP: anxiety, depression and severe bipolar disorder; which were diagnosed in November 2015 by a physician. On approximately April 2016, the pt visited websites that contained vaccine description and side effects information. In the seven years preceding his zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination to the present, pt had received inpatient or outpatient care, he also had required hospitalization or recurrent medical care and treatment or medication for bipolar disorder, anxiety and depression (2013-2019 and 2019-present), asthma (2017-present) (onset date: unknown, outcome: not recovered), and Alzheimer's (2017-present) (onset date: unknown, outcome: not recovered). In the seven years preceding his zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccination to the present, pt was prescribed with amoxicillin for asthma (only on 06-NOV-2019), "donopentin" for Alzheimer's (2017-present), and bupropion for bipolar disorder, anxiety and depression (2014-2019 and 2019-present). At the time of this report, the outcome of pain, pyrexia, blister, scab, varicella and herpes zoster was unknown; while the outcome of bipolar disorder, depression and anxiety were not recovered. The reporter considered the claimed events to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).     Upon internal review, bipolar disorder and dementia Alzheimer's type were determined to be medically significant events.
CUR_ILL: Anxiety; Bipolar disorder; Depression; Mental disability; Non-tobacco user

A few days after getting the shot, I started breaking out in vesicles on my lower legs.  They were extremely itchy, had yellow fluid oozing from them. Very comparable to a chicken pox vesicle. They continued for a couple of weeks and gradually went away.   A week after I got the shot, I did go in to see an NP and she didn't seem too concerned, just to let them run their course (I was worried about them being contagious).  Fast forward to 12/2/2020, I had an appt to get the 2nd dose. I was pretty leery about getting it, worried about having another reaction. I showed the pictures to the nurse before I got the shot and she said it definitely looked like shingles. She did consult with the doctor and the pharmacist there, and after researching, the pharmacist said it is not a live virus, so it should not have been from the shot. After discussing with the nurse, I decided to wait on getting the booster.  I believe it would have been pretty coincidental to have shingles/chicken pox vesicles break out only days after getting the Shingrix vaccine.  Of note, I also have had chicken pox twice in my life.  I do have photos of the vesicles if you would like them.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Became extremely ill on Thu 10/24/19 (two days after I received the 3 vaccines). Symptoms included feeling extremely feverish and fatigued, an extremely dry throat and an unproductive cough which which felt like a sore throat mixed in with layrngitis (losing about 95% of my speaking voice), and persistent discomfort and pressure in my eyes. I was not comfortably able to speak for a week and did not retain my speaking voice for 3 weeks.  I remember feeling like these were not mild or typical flu symptoms for me because of the severity of losing my voice, how long it took to fully get my voice back, the dry non-productive cough (vs. a burning sore throat feeling that would normally result from coughing so much), and the general malaise of all the symptoms that I felt for up to 3 weeks. I took 3 days off of work because of how ill I felt and because I could not talk (Thu 10/24, Fri 10/25, and Mon 10/28). Even after coming back to work on 10/29, I felt I probably should have taken at least 2-3 more days off.   Saw my primary care physician on Tue 10/29/19 to discuss my symptoms and obtain a work absence excuse note for having missed previous days (per my employer). No treatment was administered or medications prescribed. His notes indicate: "discussed typical resolution, warning symptoms reviewed"   Saw the same primary care physician again on Mon 11/11/19 for a physical. I mentioned that in hindsight, I thought these vaccines may have contributed to my falling ill but was told in a very short and muffled response, "I don't think so". There was no further conversation in regards to this because his response swayed me based on his position of expertise but also how uncomfortable I felt. However, he did not document this specific inquiry on my appointment notes. I felt later on after my 3 weeks of feeling ill that these vaccines most likely made me ill and that I should have pushed the conversation. The obvious connection between the vaccines and becoming ill two days later is a glaring concern for me. The Comprehensive Metabolic Panel and Lipid Panel blood test results I did that day came back ok with no concerns and no need for follow up.
LAB_DATA: The Comprehensive Metabolic Panel and Lipid Panel blood test results I did on 11/11/19 for my yearly phyisical came back ok with no concerns and no need for follow up.
OTHER_MEDS: CBD capules (brand Trace) and Suan Zao Ren Tang (brand Evergreen), B-Complex, Magnesium, Multivitamin
CUR_ILL: Anesthesia of skin, Paresthesia of skin

cardiovascular event; vision issues; balance problems; This spontaneous report has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation, concerning a patient of unknown age and gender. On an unknown date, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, lot expiration date, dosage, anatomical location and route of administration were not provided), for routine health maintenance and its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after vaccination, the patient suffered a cardiovascular event (cardiovascular disorder), vision issues (visual impairment) and balance problems (balance disorder). As a result of those symptoms, the patient was seen and treated by medical providers was still under their care. As a direct and proximate result, the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. The cardiovascular disorder, visual impairment and balance disorder were considered disabling events.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Likely had the shot administered very deeply, causing mechanical and chemical irritation of the posterior humeral head; Placed relatively high on her left upper arm; Lytic lesion in the proximal humerus; SIRVA; Adhesive capsulitis; This literature case was received on 24-Nov-2020 and concerned an adult, female patient. The patient was 51-year-old at 10-month presentation post vaccination.   The patient's concurrent condition included prolapsing mitral valve. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. The patient had no history of shoulder issues and was able to work out and play recreational level sports before the flu shot. The patient was a healthy, fit woman with no significant medial or surgical history.   On an unknown date in Sep-2016, the patient was vaccinated with influenza virus vaccine polyvalent (brand not specified, anatomical location: left posterior deltoid, distal and slightly anterior to the posterolateral border of the acromion, also reported high on her left upper arm, dose, route of administration: not reported) for influenza vaccination. The batch number was not reported. The patient likely had the shot administered very deeply, causing mechanical and chemical irritation of the posterior humeral head (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine administered at inappropriate site' and 'Inappropriate route of vaccination').   On an unknown date in 2016, one day after receiving influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, the patient developed left shoulder symptoms. The patient later experienced unremitting left shoulder pain and loss of motion.   On 13-Oct-2016, two weeks after receiving flu shot, the patient presented to a primary care sports medicine (PCSM) specialist. On presentation, anteroposterior radiograph of the left shoulder was unremarkable showing no evidence of a lesion in the posterior proximal humerus.   On 08-Nov-2016, two months after the flu shot, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) demonstrated a partial-thickness rotator cuff tear with a small hyperintense area on the posterior aspect of the rotator cuff footprint.   The differential diagnosis included infection, traumatic injury, or immunologic reactive inflammation. Her shoulder pain was managed conservatively, with a course of anti-inflammatory medications and physical therapy.  On an unspecified date in 2016, approximately three months after the flu shot, during the conservative treatment course of anti-inflammatory medications and physical therapy, the patient developed adhesive capsulitis. An ultrasound guided joint aspiration was performed and the sample was evaluated for the presence of aerobic and anaerobic bacteria, fungi, and mycobacteria. Ten aerobic bacterial cultures demonstrated no growth after five days of incubation. Ten anaerobic cultures had no growth after 14 days of incubation. Nine fungal cultures had no growth after four weeks of incubation, and seven cultures for mycobacteria had no growth after eight weeks of incubation. This was treated with two ultrasound-guided intraarticular cortisone steroid injections. Because of the presence of a prolapsing mitral valve, two blood cultures were obtained, which showed no growth. In addition, serologic studies for Lyme disease were negative (both immunoglobulin G and immunoglobulin M Enzyme Immunoassay (EIA)). Studies for rheumatologic disease, including antinuclear antibodies, rheumatoid factor, and human leukocyte antigen-B27, were also negative.  On an unspecified date in 2017, ten months after the flu shot, the patient's presenting symptoms included anterior and lateral shoulder pain, pain with shoulder flexion and abduction, and night pain. She denied paresthesias, fevers, chills, and night sweats. On presentation to physician's office, she had tenderness to palpation over the anterior fibers of the supraspinatus, with no evidence of muscle wasting. She had normal shoulder range of motion (ROM), with the exception of diminished active abduction (100 degrees on left vs. 170 degrees on right) and internal rotation (5 spinal levels less than the right side). Her strength examination was normal, with the exception of infraspinatus weakness (4/5).  On 12-Jul-2017, ten months after the flu shot and eight months after the initial MRI, a repeat MRI was obtained which demonstrated a significant increase in the signal within the humeral head with bony erosion. Given the change in MRI appearance, she was referred to an infectious disease specialist who recommended rheumatologic blood work (inflammatory markers, metabolic panelsï¿½) and a computed tomography (CT) scan. The lab, including an erythrocyte sedimentation rate and C-reactive protein, were normal.   On 28-Aug-2017, the CT scan demonstrated a large lytic lesion in the posterior proximal humerus. A CT-guided needle biopsy of the bone and soft tissue performed at that time (11 months from the flu shot) was inconclusive.  On an unspecified date in Oct-2017, 13 months after the flu shot, the patient had left shoulder arthroscopy with bone and soft-tissue biopsy and debridement. At the time of arthroscopy, there was evidence of patchy synovitis in the joint with a focal synovitic area at the site of the lytic lesion and a bone defect in the posterior aspect of the humeral head, adjacent to the infraspinatus insertion. Tissue cultures were taken from throughout the anterior capsule, posterior capsule, and synovium. A spinal needle was then used to localize the defect, and an incision was made for insertion of a 7 mm core biopsy needle. The core biopsy was taken from this defect, with debridement of unhealthy-appearing tissue in and at the edges of the defect. Additionally, tissue samples were taken from various locations within the joint. All cultures came back negative. Each location shared inflammatory features of varying degrees. Tissue from the anterior capsule consisted of synovium that showed papillary hypertrophy with a moderate degree of hyperplasia of the synovial lining layer. There was a moderate degree of chronic lymphoplasmacytic inflammation that had a high proportion of plasma cells, some of which contained more than one nucleus. Tissue from the posterior capsule, adjacent to the bone erosion, also showed papillary hypertrophy with greater degrees of hyperplasia and chronic inflammation imparting a much higher degree of cellularity including lymphocytes, plasma cells, and stromal elements. Tissue from the defect in the posterior aspect of the humeral head showed inflammatory destruction of the articular cartilage and bone. The superficial cartilage showed inflammatory destruction of the cartilage with Weichselbaum lacunae and a small amount of pannus. The bony endplate was focally destroyed, and the bone while eroded was demonstrating remodelling activity. The marrow space showed replacement of the fat by dense and loose fibrous and fibromyxoid tissue associated with a variable dense inflammatory infiltrate that was composed of lymphocytes and plasma cells, some of which, as elsewhere, contained more than one nucleus.  Once the area of inflammatory tissue was removed and healthy bone/tissue was stimulated at the time of arthroscopy, the patient's body was able to mount a response to heal the injured area. Postoperatively, the patient was placed into a sling for immobilization for two weeks, followed by the initiation of shoulder ROM exercises. Once full ROM was obtained, a supervised shoulder strengthening program was begun.   On an unknown date in 2018, at 1-year follow-up, the patient recovered from all events. She had regained full passive and active ROM in all directions, and strength and functional capacity have returned to normal. No new imaging was obtained given her full functional status with no complaints.  The reporters assessed the events of 'osteolytic lesion', 'shoulder injury related to vaccine administration' and 'adhesive capsulitis' as related to influenza virus vaccine polyvalent. Based on a strong temporal relationship between the influenza vaccination, placed relatively high on her left upper arm, and the onset of patient's left shoulder symptoms the day after the injection, there was a concern that her symptoms were related to the injection.  The events of 'osteolytic lesion', 'shoulder injury related to vaccine administration' and 'adhesive capsulitis' were considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus' Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.   Company comment: A 51-year-old female patient started experiencing symptoms, which will later be determined as osteolysis, shoulder injury (related to vaccine administration) and periarthritis, one day after administration of influenza virus vaccine polyvalent in the area described as: left posterior deltoid, distal and slightly anterior to the posterolateral border of the acromion, also reported as 'high on her left upper arm'. Reportedly, the patient likely had the shot administered very deeply, causing mechanical and chemical irritation of the posterior humeral head (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine administered at inappropriate site' and 'Inappropriate route of vaccination'). The patient's concurrent condition included prolapsing mitral valve, while concomitant medications were not reported. She had no history of shoulder issues and was able to work out and play recreational level sports before the flu shot. It was also reported that she was a healthy, fit woman with no significant medial or surgical history. Causality is assessed as possibly related for all 3 events (having in mind detailed and comprehensive diagnostics (both visual and laboratory - microbiological, inflammatory, metabolic) which excluded any other confounder) but also related to medication error. Incorrect route of product administration and product administered at inappropriate site are assessed as unrelated per company conventions.; Reporter's Comments: Based on a strong temporal relationship between the influenza vaccination, placed relatively high on her left upper arm, and the onset of patient's left shoulder symptoms the day after the injection, there was a concern that her symptoms were related to the injection.; Sender's Comments: A 51-year-old female patient started experiencing symptoms, which will later be determined as osteolysis, shoulder injury (related to vaccine administration) and periarthritis, one day after administration of influenza virus vaccine polyvalent in the area described as: left posterior deltoid, distal and slightly anterior to the posterolateral border of the acromion, also reported as 'high on her left upper arm'. She had no history of shoulder issues and was able to work out and play recreational level sports before the flu shot. It was also reported that she was a healthy, fit woman with no significant medial or surgical history. Causality is assessed as possibly related for all 3 events (having in mind detailed and comprehensive diagnostics (both visual and laboratory - microbiological, inflammatory, metabolic) which excluded any other confounder) but also related to medication error. Could not be awakened / taken to the hospital; Diarrhea; Vomiting; felt blah; Felt feverish; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of unconscious in a 50-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 13th July 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 13th July 2020, immediately after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced fever and malaise. In July 2020, the patient experienced diarrhea and vomiting. On 29th July 2020, the patient experienced unconscious (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant). In August 2020, the outcome of the unconscious, fever, diarrhea and vomiting were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the malaise was unknown.   The reporter considered the unconscious, fever, diarrhea, vomiting and malaise to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient stated immediately after having the 1st shot of Shingrix, the patient felt feverish and blah.  It worsened over the next few days and she started to have diarrhea and vomiting.  On 29th July 2020, she could not be awakened so she was taken to the hospital where she was admitted for two days.  Her doctors determined she had a bad adverse reaction to the Shingrix shot. All symptoms were resolved around mid of August 2020. The reporter consented to follow up. Emergency room visit required.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am writing because this is the second time it happens, and my doctor treats like nonchallant.  It happened when I got the first shot of VARIVAX (June 26, 2020), I broke into bump symptoms that look like chicken pox, they were raised fluid bumps a few, no more than 10 spread around my chest, neck and head. They did not itch or burn, only lasted for 5 days and were gone.  I let the time passed and got the 2nd dosage, though it was not within 60 days, the nurse said it was ok. So, I got the 2nd dosage for the VARIVAX - nothing happened in the office, I went home and  continued with normal activities. It was not until almost 2 weeks later that I started to itch, at first I didn't pay much attention but as the days went by it started to itch more. First started in my stomach, then it spread to my side trunks, then to my armpits. It is raised looked like hives - hot the touch. It started to itch, and more started coming out. It is now... on both arms, sides, butt, armpits. See pictures attached, they itch, very itchy.  I called my doctor, but he didn't do much... he just said I had a reaction to the vaccine and that it will go away. Then, he said he would call a dermatologist but so far have not heard anything. I have been taking Benadryl but that doesn't help so I stop taking it, then I put calamine lotion but that only helps for 5 minutes then it itches again.  I have pictures that I took that I would like to share.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Began feeling lightheaded on drive home, about 10-15 minutes after the injection. Breathing rate increased - I wouldn't describe it as shortness of breath, more like an anxiety reaction. Lightheadedness increased when I got out of the vehicle to swap seats with my wife so she could drive. I lost consciousness as I was reaching the passenger side door, regained almost immediately after hitting the ground. Paramedics arrived, took vital signs. Blood pressure was reading 127/89, blood sugar 68. Not sure what my resting heart rate was. Nothing was found to be alarming enough at the time to require transport or hospitalization, so I went home and rested. One additional dizzy spell occurred upon standing about four hours after the event, but cleared up after sitting down, and no further events occurred after that.
LAB_DATA: BP check, heart rate check, and blood sugar check in the field by paramedics 12/5/2020.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient started feeling her finger tips numb about 3 days after taking her vaccination. Consulted with her PCP that did not do anything at the time. In the beginning of September the symptoms got worse. Her fingers she can not move then or do anything. Then her arms started getting numb, and painful. It is from her fingers up to her neck. Her fingers are mostly numb. After some weeks she started having problems walking. Her daughter had to buy her a wheelchair. She can't move her head very well and she can't take care of her primary daily activities by herself as taking a shower, going to the bathroom, she can't dress herself without help, wash dishes doing nothing. She also got depressed, crying a lot and a family family member told her to talk to her PCP who referred her to a specialist and she does not remember her name. She said the specialist prescribed her some pills that are helping her with depression. Patient said the pain at the injection site is so severe she can't wear long sleeves. A Sleeve touching the site is very painful to her. She also says her fingers are swollen and she said she does not feel them anymore. She states she does not have any mobility in both arms. She was prescribed physical therapy but she does not believe it is helping.
LAB_DATA: She said she had some done but she does not remember dates

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2 days after the vaccine I began to experience extreme decreased appetite, on and off numbness/weakness in my extremities, restless leg, heart palpitations, shortness of breath, extreme anxiety, depression, and OCD, weightloss, upset stomach/loose stools,  dizziness/ as if I was rocking on a boat that was and still is present but manageable with Physical Therapy and other treatment.  None of these symptoms did I ever struggle with until the vaccine event. At the time of the vaccine I was a healthy 19 year old, full time college student and part time nanny. I was very active in my school's community and was very active. I went from working out 5-6 times a week to getting breathless going up a few stairs and extreme weakness. I lost about 10ish pounds, but keep in mind I am 5'3 and prior to the vaccine was around 123-125 pounds.   While many of my symptoms have gotten better, it was not without running all around to the cardiologist, ENT, SEVERAL visits to my pediatricians office of which the doctors did not listen to me. I did not get the help I needed to start feeling better until I started seeing Dr. and Dr.
LAB_DATA: ALL types of blood tests, urine tests, stomach tests, hair tests (to check for heavy metals).   Blood tests showed that I had some low vitamin levels all of which I am taking supplements for now.  Urine tests showed low levels of which can be obtained from Dr.   Stomach tests showed that I have SIBO (Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth) which went untreated for YEARS by my pediatrician Dr. at clinic. Also, I have read and been told that people with gut absorption issues and conditions such as SIBO should not receive vaccinations until the stomach condition is treated.  Hair test showed that I had some presence of heavy metals in my body which is ironic because I am led to believe that the vaccines contain aluminum and mercury amongst other awful ingredients.
CUR_ILL: None. Had not been ill in years.
ALLERGIES: Allergen to Cingular, Xyzal, and Peanuts/Treenuts

could not move / legs / had to pick up her thigh (with her arms); I could not walk 12 hours after the shot / not able to properly clean herself/ had to hold onto the wall and dresser so she could walk.; had wicked vertigo; had to urinate / and peed on the kitchen floor; She was not able to properly clean herself or the floor; muscles were so weak she could not stand/ lack of muscle strength; could not stand without assistance; she was afraid (because of this episode); still has "myalgia."; lack of energy; having urinary urgency issues / within 10 minutes she will have to urinate again; lower digestive issues / descending and sigmoid colon are making themselves known; GI upset; wasn't / diarrhea it was/ "oozing 24 hours a day 7 days a week" every time she bent over; had no solid stools during this time; stool to be black.; experiencing double vision.; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of movement disorder in a 62-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included multiple sclerosis (in remission for ten years). Previously administered products included Shingrix with an associated reaction of injection site pain (1st dose received on unknown date, for tolerance refer case US2020AMR238525). Concurrent medical conditions included immunocompromised (because of the Multiple sclerosis) and gluten sensitivity (eliminated soy, corn, and dairy from diet). Concomitant products included naltrexone.   On an unknown date, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. In November 2020, less than a year after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced gastrointestinal upset, fecal incontinence, loose stools, black stools and double vision. On an unknown date, the patient experienced movement disorder, unable to walk, vertigo, urinary incontinence, activities of daily living impaired, muscle weakness, difficulty in standing, fear, myalgia, loss of energy, urinary urgency and lower gastrointestinal disorder. The patient was treated with bismuth subsalicylate (Pepto Bismol). On an unknown date, the outcome of the movement disorder, unable to walk, vertigo, urinary incontinence, activities of daily living impaired, difficulty in standing, fear, gastrointestinal upset, loose stools and double vision were unknown and the outcome of the muscle weakness, myalgia, loss of energy, urinary urgency and lower gastrointestinal disorder were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the fecal incontinence and black stools were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the movement disorder, unable to walk, vertigo, urinary incontinence, activities of daily living impaired, muscle weakness, difficulty in standing, fear, gastrointestinal upset, fecal incontinence, loose stools, black stools, double vision, myalgia, loss of energy, urinary urgency and lower gastrointestinal disorder to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported, however could be 61 or 62 years. The patient reported she had a significant adverse reaction involving multiple body systems following the 2nd vaccine and would like to discuss it with her physician at their appointment tomorrow. The reporter requested to email the list of ingredients in the vaccine and suspension solution so that they could start discussion about possible remedies. Upon follow received on 1st December 2020 it was reported that the patient had medical history of multiple sclerosis (MS) and had been in remission for ten years. The patient stated that she was immune compromised (because of the multiple sclerosis) but was not taking any immunosuppressant medications. She had gluten sensitivity and had eliminated soy, corn, and dairy from her diet. The patient was a massage therapist for 20 years. The concomitant medications included Naturethyroid, thyroid medication made for the patient by compounding pharmacy using veggie caps. The compounding pharmacy also made the patient Naltrexone low dose 4.5 mg oral (capsules). She took 1 each night and had been taking this since 2013 for her multiple sclerosis and has not had an multiple sclerosis flare in the 7 years since she has been on this product. The patient said that she could not walk 12 hours after the 2nd shot. Around 1 am she got up to go pee and had wicked vertigo. She grabbed onto the door (to stabilizer herself) and urinated quite a bit into the toilet. She said she had to hold onto the wall and dresser so she could walk. As she was trying to walk to the kitchen, to get a glass of water, she could not move her legs. She had to pick up her thigh (with her arms) to move her legs until she got to kitchen sink to get a glass water. Then she had to urinate again and peed on the kitchen floor. The patient's muscles were so weak she could not stand without assistance. She was able to reach a stool and rested on the stool for about 15 minutes. She was not able to properly clean herself or the floor. She said she was afraid because of this episode and was ready to call 911 because she lived alone. The patient eventually made it back to bed without the glass of water. From 13th November 2020 to 25th November 2020, the patient had gastrointestinal upset. She said it was not really diarrhea it was more like an oozing 24 hours a day 7 days a week every time she bent over. She went through many (urinary/sanitary) pads and took Pepto Bismol for 2 days. She would take Pepto each time after having an ooze. The patient had no solid stools during this time and said the Pepto caused her stool to be black. The patient also reported experiencing double vision. The patient was asked her how she was feeling on the day of reporting, if her symptoms had resolved and the patient said that she still had myalgia. Groin pain; Knee pain on the right side; Upper pain in his arms; Elevated c-reactive proteins; unable to move both arms; Diagnosed with Polymyalgia Rheumatica; Unable to move both arms; Myalgia; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of polymyalgia rheumatica in a 70-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 9th September 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced polymyalgia rheumatica (serious criteria GSK medically significant), paralysis of arms (serious criteria GSK medically significant), myalgia, groin pain, knee pain, pain in arm, c-reactive protein increased and mobility decreased. On an unknown date, the outcome of the polymyalgia rheumatica, paralysis of arms, c-reactive protein increased and mobility decreased were unknown and the outcome of the myalgia, groin pain, knee pain and pain in arm were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the polymyalgia rheumatica, paralysis of arms, myalgia, groin pain, knee pain, pain in arm, c-reactive protein increased and mobility decreased to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were received as follows: The reporter was the wife of the patient and also a nurse.  Myalgia presented 2 to 3 days after the vaccine and continued throughout the month of October.  He visited a doctor on 15th September 20.  He had groin pain and knee pain on the right side.  He was referred to an orthopedist and had 4 appointments.  The knee pain was thought to be referred pain from the groin.  He had a shot in his knee on 2nd October 20 and 8th October 20.  On 15th Oct 20 and 28th October 20 he was seen for upper pain in his arms.  He was unable to move both arms.  He visited a rheumatologist  on 5h November 2020 and blood work showed elevated c-reactive proteins. He was diagnosed with Polymyalgia rheumatica. The reporter consented to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: felt like her lips were numb; left ear pressure; left jaw numbness; drooling; Mld left sided headache; left sided lower facial muscle weakness; left sided lower facial muscle weakness / diagnosed / left sided bell's palsy / facial drooping; had left ear pain; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of bell's palsy in a 61-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number J2N44, expiry date 17th May 2022) and (batch number 7TB74, expiry date 17th May 2022) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included cervical cancer, thyroid papillary carcinoma, chronic back pain, thyroid gland cancer and hysterectomy. Concurrent medical conditions included hypertension. Concomitant products included thyroxine sodium (Levothyroxine), amitriptyline and amlodipine.   On 18th November 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, the dose was an unknown dose. In November 2020, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced bell's palsy (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and ear pain. On 18th November 2020, the patient experienced numb lips, sensation of pressure in ear, numbness facial, drooling, headache and facial muscle weakness. The patient was treated with prednisone and valaciclovir (Valacyclovir). On an unknown date, the outcome of the bell's palsy, numb lips, sensation of pressure in ear, numbness facial, drooling, headache and facial muscle weakness were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the ear pain was recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the bell's palsy, ear pain, numb lips, sensation of pressure in ear, numbness facial, drooling, headache and facial muscle weakness to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information received as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient received Shingrix in left deltoid and had left ear pain for less than 3 days. She stated that, on the day of vaccination for the past hour she felt like her lips were numb and she went to an urgent care that day within an hour or so of reporting her concerns and reported that she had left ear pressure and left jaw numbness and a little bit of drooling.  She had a mild left sided headache.  Her diagnosis was left sided lower facial muscle weakness including the left side of her mouth and lower left side of her face without anything on the right side.  She was diagnosed with left sided bell's palsy on 24th November 2020.  She was prescribed prednisone 60 mg. daily for 7 days and 1 gram of valacyclovir three times per day for 7 days.  On27th November 2020, she was taking the prescribed medication and she felt that her symptoms were the same but no new symptoms.  On 30th November 20, she reported feeling that there was slight improvement in her facial drooping.  She had a recent primary care visit on 21st Octo 20 with no mention of any concern.   The reporter consented to follow up. Lot number provided was listed in the patient's medical chart with two separate vials for the vaccine.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Cervical cancer; Chronic back pain; Hysterectomy; Thyroid gland cancer; Thyroid papillary carcinoma

On an unknown date in Nov-2020, the patient developed serious sweats from flu shot (hyperhidrosis), chills, fever (pyrexia), pain 2 out of 10 at is left lower abdomen site (infusion site pain) and red dots, dryness underneath subcutaneous Remodulin site dressing (dermatitis contact) (unknown latency) following administration of INFLUENZA VACCINE, TREPROSTINIL SODIUM and SELEXIPAG.  It was reported that the patient discontinued Uptravi while in the hospital and transitioned to Remodulin.  It was reported that the patient was admitted to the hospital for starting Remodulin and was discharged on 17-Nov-2020.  Action taken with Remodulin, INFLUENZA and Uptravi was not reported for the events of infusion site pain and dermatitis. Action taken with Remodulin was not applicable for the events of chills, pyrexia, and hyperhidrosis. Action taken with Flu and Uptravi was not reported for the events of chills, pyrexia and hyperhidrosis.   It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  At the time of reporting, the outcome of chills, pyrexia and hyperhidrosis was considered as recovering while the outcome of events infusion site pain and dermatitis contact was unknown.  The reporter assessed the causal relationship between the Remodulin and the events of chills, pyrexia and hyperhidrosis as not related. The reporter did not provide causality for the events of infusion site pain and dermatitis contact.  Case Comment/Senders Comment: The company has assessed the serious adverse event of chills, pyrexia, and hyperhidrosis as not related to treprostinil and likely related to flu shot.  Information on lot number was requested for this case.; Sender's Comments: This case concerns 53 years old male patient who had chills, pyrexia, hyperhidrosis, infusion site pain and dermatitis contact after administration of INFLUENZA VACCINE and while being treated with REMODULIN and UPTRAVI. The time to onset is compatible. Additional information regarding medical history, concurrent condition and lab data excluding other predisposing etiologies would be needed for complete assessment of the case. Based upon the reported information, the role of suspect products cannot be assessed.

At my first pap smear when I was around age 21, it came back abnormal. One year later at my next pap smear, it was abnormal again and we tested for HPV. The HPV test came back positive. I decided to come back after 6 months to monitor the situation as I was close to cervical cancer. After 6 months, my pap smear came back normal. I came back again after 6 months and this time, my pap smear was so abnormal that my OBGYN wanted to do a cervical biopsy that day. The results came back and I was extremely close to having cervical cancer. I had to have a  LEEP surgery to remove the abnormal cells. I will have difficulty getting pregnant now and may go into early labor. When we tested the strain of HPV I had, it was a strain that Gardasil is supposed to protect against.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Dizziness, whole body muscle aches (extreme like a bad flu), and nausea.  Dizziness noticed early a.m. when first woke up the day after the vaccine., but had difficulty sleeping due to muscle aches.  Dizziness /vertigo was bad enough to require me to lay down for the rest of the day Saturday. Needed some help walking early on, but that gradually improved  to where I could walk /stand up as long as I had something to hold onto (wall or counter, etc).  I was only able to eat toast and ramen .  Couldn't read or watch tv, too dizzy.  By the next morning (12/6/2020), muscle aches and nausea was gone but I still suffered dizziness if I moved too fast or bent over or turned my head. I could function, but was tired and "not quite right."  Still experienced very slight dizziness by Monday 12/7, continuing throughout that day, but manageable.   Today  12/8, I'm not quite feeling 100% but hopefully soon. Luckily I never need another dose of Shingrix!
LAB_DATA: None.  It occurred on a weekend.  Did not seem urgent enough to go to Urgent Care or ER during a pandemic.  I did message my Dr. on Monday but by then I was feeling much better. FYI - I had a fever of 100.7 and muscle aches for1 day after the first Shingrix dose a few months ago -- but no dizziness that time.

Patient started having a minor seizure immediately after the flu shot was injected. He was shaking, dizzy, and his skin began to feel clammy and cold. The shaking would stop and start again. He was breathing and upright the whole time. The ambulance was called right after the reaction began. When paramedics arrived they tested the patients blood glucose, which was normal. His blood pressure was very low, but I don't know the exact numbers. They monitored blood pressure for several minutes and said they weren't leaving until his blood pressure came up. The patient said he was not on any medications and had not had anything to eat since breakfast. He admitted that he was not very well hydrated. He said he had a similar reaction to one of his Gardasil shots, but has never had a reaction to any other vaccine including the flu shot. The patient eventually left the pharmacy area on his own will after about a half an hour, the paramedics said that they needed his brother to take him to urgent care right away since he did not want to go in the ambulance. That is all the information I have at this time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 11/4/2020, she received Menveo #2 and Bexsero #1. The next day had arm pain on left arm, which lasted a whole week. On the 6th, had numbness on anterior right lateral calf, which lasted about a day. Overnight and into the next day, she developed nausea and globus sensation.  On Sunday the 8th, went to restaurant and after eating, she was feeling increasingly nauseous but didn't throw up. Felt like she couldn't breathe. No one else was sick. Once at home, she kept gagging. Dizzy. ED: ibuprofen and nausea meds ODT (has used a few, but they didn't help at all). Had had blood work drawn the same day Broke out in a rash around the same time- seen here and Dx Urticaria. Never took the cetirizine because rash self-resolved after about 1 week of intermittent coming and going. No rash for past 2 weeks.  Seen here on 11/12. Urgent Care visit on either the 17th/18th who recommended PMD follow-up. Last Thursday 11/19 called, but never got a call back. So Mom came by yesterday to get this appointment.  At this time, she continues to have spitting up - clear - no blood, occasionally feels like a luggie is stuck in throat and can't cough it up. Denies abdominal or chest pain. Diarrhea started around same time as spitting and ongoing with TID BMs that are liquid - no blood.  Dizziness happening at random and worse when standing up. Drinking water (about 2 cups/day) and juice (about 1 cup/day). Also not eating well initially because of globus sensation, which has resolved, so now feels like she can eat again. In middle of drinking, she'll get hit with sensation to spit up.
LAB_DATA: 11/6/2020: CMP and CBC/d - WNL 12/4/2020: RFP, HFP, Lipase, Amylase - WNL; Allergy panel + timothy grass and milk (asymptomatic),; ESR 22; CRP 10.1

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe pain in the immunization arm on exertion. Per the patient, pain is a 9.5/10 when he lifts things with the immunization arm

The patient answered "yes" on the immunization screening consent form for the question: Have you ever had a serious reaction or fainted after receiving a vaccination? She reported that she had fainted after a flu shot a long time ago, but was willing to proceed with the flu shot when she asked. She was counseled to remain in the vaccination room for a few minutes after the immunization was administered. She was moved to the lobby to continue waiting the remaining 15 to 20 minutes. Shortly after she returned to the counter to report that her tongue and throat were swelling. She reported at this time that she had experienced an anaphylactic reaction to some allergy shots when she was younger, and this "feels the same." We immediately called for emergency assistance and brought her into our vaccination room. As per protocol, she was given 1 dose 0.3 mg of epinephrine by IM administration and her blood pressure and heart rate were checked. She confirmed the absence of any hives or itching so we did not administer diphenhydramine.  Emergency assistance arrived and after speaking with the patient and listening to our report,  she was transported to the emergency room for further evaluation and continued monitoring.
ALLERGIES: No known allergies to medications or food

permanent scarring; a severe and painful shingles outbreak; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. As a direct and proximate result of defective zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of the vaccination, she suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.

Sepsis, neonatal, other specified bacteria; Foetal exposure during pregnancy; respiratory distress; Hypothermia; Feeding problems; 42 3/7 weeks born; This spontaneous prospective preganncy report was received from a physician and refers to a 1-day-old male patient.   On 16-AUG-2017, the 17-year-old mother of the patient was was vaccinated with a first dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9), intramuscularly in the right deltoid (lot # M040412, expiration date was not reported but upon internal validation established as 30-JUN-2019; strength and dose were not reported). On the same day, his mother was vaccinated with the first dose of meningococcal b rfhbp vaccine (e. coli) (TRUMENBA), intramuscularly in the left deltoid (lot # S26985; strength, dose and expiration date were not reported) and the second dose of meningococcal acyw conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA), intramuscularly, in the left deltoid (lot # 45539AA; strength, dose and expiration date were not reported). The mother was unaware of being pregnant. According to mother's report, on the same day, she requested oral birth contraceptive (OBC), denied being sexually active and stated that her last menstrual period was on 28-JUL-2017 (also reported as 3 weeks early July 2017). Therefore, she was given the OBC which she took during September and October in 2018. On 25-OCT-2017, the mother returned for the second dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9). Furthermore, on an unspecified date in 2017, she had a positive home pregnancy test; so she returned to the physician office on 09-NOV-2017 and informed about it; subsequently a blood human chorionic gonadotropin (HCG) test was performed there and was positive. She was sent to ultrasound and measured 38 weeks plus 3 days. Her estimated LMP was on 14-FEB-2017 and her estimated date of delivery would be 21-NOV-2017.  The mother had her first prenatal visit on 14-NOV-2017 (she was tested for human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and Syphilis then) and her last prenatal visit on 06-DEC-2017. There were not risk factors in this pregnancy. She had no infections during pregnancy. She had antibody screen negative, Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) negative, serology non-reactive, HIV negative, group B streptococcus (GBS) negative, gonorrhea test (GC) negative and Chlamydia negative. She was Rubella immune.   It was 42 week and 3 days of the mother's pregnancy. The mother had an induction of labor, her membranes were raptured on 07-DEC-2017. Fluid was clear. The fetus was monitored externally. Maternal fever was greater than 100.4 degrees Fahrenheit. The mother received oxytocin (PITOCIN) during labor and epidural anesthesia. Also, she received three doses of ampicillin and one dose of gentamicin. Presentation of fetus was vertex. The labor was prolonged and it took 22 hours and 36 minutes. The baby was born vaginally. The infant had initial respiratory distress but transitioned quickly post delivery. In the delivery room the baby was stimulated. Suctioned with a bulb. The patient had Apgar score 8 at one minute and 9 at five minutes. His birthweight was 3700 grams. His head circuit (circ) was 36.00 cm, his body temperature was 36.33 Celsius degrees; pulse rate was 134 (unit not provided), respiratory (Resp) rate was 46 (unit not provided), glucose was 61 (unit not provided), "Dia" was 41 (unit not provided), pulse oximetry (Ox) was 100 (unit not provided). On the same day, the patient was admitted to newborn intensive care unit (NICU) from newborn nursery as he had suspected sepsis and required intensive monitoring and observation for signs/symptoms of clinical sepsis. He was transferred to NICU in crib and placed on pre-warm radiant warmer (RW). His admission physical exam showed: GENERAL: awake, alert, responsive; in no acute distress; no dysmorphic features; exam consistent with gestational age assessment; HEAD/FACE: normocephalic; sutures opposed; anterior fontanel flat; EYES: red reflex present bilaterally; EARS: normally set; internal ear exam not performed; NOSE/MOUTH/THROAT: no nasal flaring; nares patent bilaterally; no cleft; gag reflex present; NECK/THYROID: supple; LYMPHATIC: no adenopathy noted; BREAST: normal for gestational age; RESPIRATORY: no retractions noted; breath sounds clear and equal with good air exchange; CARDIO/VASCULAR: S1, S2 normal; no murmur appreciated; regular rate and rhythm; pulses equal; ABDOMEN: bowel sounds present; soft, non-tender without masses; no hepatosplenomegaly; GASTROINTESTINAL (GU)/RECTAL: testes descended bilaterally; anus patent; SKIN/HAIR: large port wine stain to right leg; BACK/SPINE: no abnormalities noted; no sacral dimple; MUSCULOSKELETAL/EXTREMITIES: no deformities noted; hips stable; moves all extremities symmetrically; NEUROLOGICAL: reflexes 2+ and symmetric; muscle tone appropriate for gestational age; White Blood Cells (WBC): 14.6 (unit not provided); Hemoglobin/Hematocrit (H/H): 16.1/48 (unit not provided); Platelet (Plt): 349000 (unit not provided); "I:T": 0.14 (unit not provided); C-reactive protein (CRP): 10.1(unit not provided), increased. At the admission, the patient's temperature was 36.2 Celsius degrees. The diagnosis was hypothermia, newborn. The patient was at risk for hypoglycaemia and required intensive monitoring and observation for need for continued thermoregulation. He received fluid administration (reported as sweetease) through peripheral intravenous catheter (right hand) and he tolerated procedure well with good pain management. RW was maintained for thermoregulation. Since 08-DEC-2017, the patient had feeding problems (unspecified). He was breastfed on demand and doing well with nipple shield. On 08-DEC-2017, the patient started receiving gentamycin and ampicillin. On 10-DEC-2017, the patient had hearing screening (Automated Auditory Brainstem Response (AABR)) performed and he passed the test.  The outcome of respiratory distress was considered to be recovered on 08-DEC-2017. The outcome of the rest of the events was not provided. The causality assessment between the events and the suspect vaccines was not provided.  Upon internal review, the events of sepsis neonatal and neonatal respiratory distress was considered to be medically significant.  All available medical records will be provided upon request. Serum sickness-like reaction (SSLR); Swelling of her joints; A generalized urticarial rash; High fever; Worsening Arthralgia; Initial information was received on 27-Oct-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case from other healthcare professional issued in a literature article.   Literature abstract- Case Description: A 4-year-old female developed a generalized urticarial rash with swelling of her joints six days after receiving MMR, varicella, DTaP, and IPV vaccines. She was started on prednisolone by her pediatrician for presumed SSLR however was subsequently admitted with high fevers and worsening arthralgia. Her CRP, procalcitonin and ESR were all elevated and her respiratory viral panel was positive for adenovirus. Her complement levels(C3, C4) were normal. IV methylprednisolone was started with dramatic improvement and resolution in symptomatology over the course of 48 hours.She was diagnosed with SSLR due to routine vaccinations and was discharged on a prednisone taper with instructions to space out vaccinations in the future to elicit the causal vaccine.  Discussion: SSLR's are usually attributed to medications and self-resolve after discontinuation of the offending agent. SSLR due to MMR, varicella, DTaP, and IPV vaccinations have not yet been described in literature. Refractory or severe symptoms with high fever, debilitating arthralgia, and persistent urticaria can be treated with prednisone.    This case involves a four years old female patient who experienced serum sickness-like reaction (SSLR) (Serum sickness-like reaction), generalized urticarial rash (urticaria), swelling of joints (joint swelling), high fever (pyrexia) and arthralgia (arthralgia), while she received vaccines POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE (INACTIVATED), DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE, VARICELLA ZOSTER VACCINE [VARICELLA VACCINE] and MEASLES VACCINE, MUMPS VACCINE, RUBELLA VACCINE [MMR].  Medical history, past medical treatments, past vaccinations, concomitant medication and family history were not provided.  On an unknown date, the patient received a dose of suspect POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE (INACTIVATED) (Produced by unknown manufacturer, lot number and expiration date were not reported) a dose of DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE (Produced by unknown manufacturer, lot number and expiration date were not reported), a dose of VARICELLA VACCINE (Not produced by Sanofi Pasteur, lot number and expiration date were not reported) and a dose of MMR (Not produced by Sanofi Pasteur, lot number and expiration date were not reported) via unknown route at an unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a serious generalized urticarial rash (urticaria) and swelling of joints (joint swelling), six days following the administration of POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE (INACTIVATED), DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE, VARICELLA VACCINE and MMR.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a high fever (pyrexia) and arthralgia (unknown latency) following the administration of POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE (INACTIVATED), DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE, VARICELLA VACCINE and MMR. On an unknown date, patient was diagnosed with serious serum sickness-like reaction (SSLR)(unknown latency) following vaccination. The patient was hospitalized for these events on an unknown date.  Relevant laboratory test results included: The results of C-reactive protein (CRP), Procalcitonin and Red blood cell Sedimentation Rate (ESR) (Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate) were elevated. Respiratory viral panel was positive for adenovirus. Complement factor C3 and C4 were normal.  Final diagnosis was serum sickness-like reaction (SSLR).  The patient was treated with PREDNISOLONE (PREDNISOLONE) for Serum sickness-like reaction. METHYLPREDNISOLONE (METHYLPREDNISOLONE) and PREDNISONE (PREDNISONE) was also given to patient during hospitalization.  The patient was recovered from all the events as there was dramatic improvement and resolution in symptomatology over the course of 48 hours. The patient was discharged from the hospital on Prednisone taper with instructions to space out vaccination in future to elicit the casual vaccine. Outcome of serum sickness-like reaction (SSLR) was not reported.  There will be no information on the batch number for this case.; Sender's Comments: This case concerns a four years old female patient who experienced serum sickness-like reaction (SSLR), urticaria, joint swelling, pyrexia and arthralgia, after vaccination with POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE (INACTIVATED) (unknown manufacturer), DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND NOS PERTUSSIS VACCINE (unknown manufacturer), VARICELLA VACCINE (other manufacturer) and MMR(other manufacturer). The time to onset is compatible for events urticaria and joint swelling and unknown for rest of the events. Laboratory data involved C-reactive protein (CRP), Procalcitonin and Red blood cell Sedimentation Rate (ESR) (Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate) all were elevated. Respiratory viral panel was positive for adenovirus and complement factor C3 and C4 were normal. The patient's medical history, medical condition at time of vaccination, concomitant medication were not reported. 11/15/2020: Hives were first discovered on stomach, arms, and legs at 5:00 am. Immediately took Benadryl 25 mg tablet. I have no allergies and have never experienced an adverse reaction to vaccines, medications, food, or health care products (such as lotion, body wash, etc.).   11/15/2020-11/16/2020: Within the first 6-12 hours, the hives began to spread to my entire body. I took one dose of Benadryl about every 4-6 hours for the first 24 hours, starting at 5:00 am when the hives were discovered on 11/15/2020. Benadryl did not provide relief. I also used calamine lotion on affected areas for the first 24 hours to calm itching.   11/16/2020: I visited my dermatologist (who I have visited before for acne but no other skin issues) at 3:15 pm who confirmed hives but could not confirm the specific cause. I provided information on the vaccine that I received (as that was the only ?new thing? that I had taken or began using  within the last few months). He instructed me to keep a detailed journal and monitor flare-ups, as well as change detergent, not use fragrances (in health care products or home products, such as Glade Plug-ins), and monitor foods that commonly cause reactions in individuals (such as strawberries). He prescribed Triamcinolone 0.1% Cream. I was also instructed to take Zyrtec 10 mg instead of Benadryl (since I was seeing no relief). He also provided the option to take Pepcid 20 mg with the Zyrtec. I began using Triamcinolone 0.1% Cream on patches of hives that night at around 6:00 pm and took a Claritin 10 mg tablet with the Pepcid 20 mg.   11/15/2020-11/17/2020: Hives covered extremities and most of body the first 48 hours after discovery. They were large patches (about 8-10 inches grouped together) and were painful, itchy welts. They moved frequently around my body and would disappear and reappear in different areas every 1-2 hours. I noticed that the hives would flare sporadically and appear in unusual places (such as tops of feet and neck), but specifically on ?touch points? (example: sitting on the couch or in the car would cause large welts on my back, butt, back of legs, and back of arms). I limited showers and would only use cool water with Aveeno fragrance-free body wash. I also kept my skin moisturized with Aveeno and CeraVe, and wore loose clothing. No pain relievers such as Advil or Tylenol were taken.  11/17/2020: Continued use of Triamcinolone 0.1% Cream and Claritin 10 mg with Pepcid 20 mg.  11/18/2020: Discontinued Triamcinolone 0.1% Cream (hives were frequently moving and I did not want to continue reapplying cream if the hives disappeared and reappeared in the same area); I also saw no relief from the cream since I began using it. I saw a good amount of improvement that morning from the Claritin and Pepcid taken over the last 48 hours; the patches were still present but they no longer covered my entire body.   11/18/2020-Present: I have continued to take Claritin 10 mg. On 12/2/2020 I discontinued the Pepcid 20 mg as it specifies on box not to take for more than 14 days. The hives have not gone away permanently, but they have improved since 11/18/2020. They continue to appear on my stomach, arms, legs, back, and butt, either in large patches or small spots that are grouped somewhat close together. It is rare that they appear on multiple areas of my body, but it has happened (for example: the night of 12/8/2020, they were on my arms, back, and butt after sitting on the couch for a few minutes). I work from home due to COVID and do not typically notice any hives during the day while I work at my desk and move around, but I tend to wake up with them in one or two areas and go to sleep with them in one or two areas. To be on the safe side, I have changed to a fragrance-free detergent and I continue to use fragrance-free body products. I have tried to keep somewhat of a detailed journal with photographs, and have found no correlation between the hives/flare ups and any food or products that I have used. I have had no other symptoms or health issues since first discovering them on 11/15/2020. I have also not taken any pain relievers, such as Advil or Tylenol, since discovering them. I'm a fairly active person but have not exercised or exerted myself much since discovering them; I only go on short walks when the weather is cool (I do not see flareups from the walks).
OTHER_MEDS: Tretinoin 0.05% Cream (applied on face, neck, and chest at night)
HISTORY: IBS and GERD (diagnosed in 2015); hiatus hernia (found in 2017 after endoscopy)

Given that this was one of the last vaccines I had received in 2013 before being diagnosed with Miller Fisher Variant Gullian Barre Syndrome in 2015. During 2014, late July, I started experiencing the lost of my voice. I thought it was sore throat, but after going weeks with no signs of getting better, I started going to different docotrs trying to find out what was wrong with me. I've made repeated trips t the ENT were I was getting a camera down my nose almost every time I went. They found nothing. It wasn't until I was recommended to go see a neurologist who after running a couple of in office test, told me to admit myself in the hospital when I've finally been diagnosed. After more being ran, spinal taps, speech pathologist, and blood transfusions all they could tell me was that what I had closely resembles Miller Fisher Variant Gullian Barre Syndrome. I can no longer speak normally, I speak with a whisper and it is harder for me to swallow food without choking. Swimming has also become more difficult for me since the back of my throat/ vocal chords are  partially paralyzed its harder for me to hold my breathe under water.
LAB_DATA: Spinal tap - 2015 IVIG infusion 2015 ; 2016 speech pathology related test - 2015; 2016
HISTORY: After receiving vaccines in year 2013-14, in the month of June 2014 I started losing my voice. After being told by my neurologist to go admit myself in the hospital I have discovered that I had Miller Fisher Gullian Barre Syndrome. My voice hasn't returned since.

The second shot was administered in the morning on 4/7/19, by the  evening I developed a moderate headache and nausea.  At approx 2:00 in the morning I woke with severe alternating chills and hot spells, my legs were shaking, headache was increased and nausea was increased.  I tried to get out of bed as I was going to vomit and couldn't stand due my legs shaking and loss of lower muscle strength.  I crawled to the backroom where I did vomit and had vertigo with extreme cold chills.  My husband assisted me back to bed where the above side effects continued until mid morning (9 am).  I was then able to sit up with continuation of a headache, nausea, profound weakness and vertigo.  This continued throughout the day until the following morning.  I was not able to go to work the day of the reaction.   I have never had a reaction to any vaccine and I have had annual influenza and required pneumococcal vaccines in the past.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediate pain and muscle stiffness over 5 days, much worse than normal soreness experienced after previous flu shots. Increasing pain and stiffness over next two weeks, to the point of constant pain with any motion with the arm over 90 degrees, any lifting, or any pushing. Career (Dance Professor) affected. All dancing/teaching had to be modified. At 5 weeks everyday activities completed limited and sought orthopedic doctor's care. Stopped dancing starting 11/13/20. Started advised 8 weeks of physical therapy on 11/24/20. Spoke to head pharmacist on 12/4/2020 who indicated I would be given a call by their Immunization Team and that she would file a VAERS report. Have not heard back, so wanted to make sure the report got filed. Also spoke to Pharmacy head feedback department who created a case file and contacted the division head of the Pharmacy location, who was supposed to call within 24 hours but has not.
LAB_DATA: Strength, range of motion, and pain tests at Orthopedic Dr. on 11/2/20. Additional physical exam with physical therapist 11/24/2020. Doctor concluded that because of location of shot (barely a centimeter below the top of shoulder) and the slenderness of my arm, that the shot was administered directly into the tendon at the shoulder joint,  at least 4 inches away from midsection of the deltoid muscle where it should have been administered. Diagnosed with tendonitis as a result of vaccine. Physical therapist concurred because of the very specific location of pain, in the supraspinatus, as opposed to usual tendonitis pain which occurs in the group of tendons. Treatment in process with physical therapist. Please let me know if you have any other questions.

Red & warm to the touch. Redness spread. Mom gave tylenol & benadryl. Also some swelling. Told to treat with Ibuprofen, oral benadryl, cool compresses. Mark the spot & follow up if there is spreading. Also come in if a fever develops or other concerns arose.

Pt. stated (R) arm was hot, Red, had a big knot that was hard like a rock, swollen & painful. Also had chills. Used ice & took Aspirin & Allertec. Started soon after vaccines & said she felt terrible the next day but today (12/9) is much better - Arm still red & has bruise but not painful or knot.
(1) Redness / itching night of vaccination @ injection site applied Benadryl cream + took Benadryl tablet  (2) symptoms lessened over next couple days

I immediately felt a "charge" go down my arm to my wrist and my wrist muscles tightened. (My wrist was fractured January 2016, the fracture subseqently "settled" followed by Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS) to that arm and hand.)  Later in the day, I used KT Tape (kinesiology tape) to help alleviate the wrist discomfort and took ibuprofen for injection site pain.   Some discomfort in my wrist continues. Injection site pain continued for more than two weeks. There continues to be occasional discomfort at the injection site.
HISTORY: ALLERGIC TO DUST, GRASS POLLEN, ANIMAL DANDER

SYMPTOM_TEXT: recurrence of shingles; she was diagnosed with shingles due to back pain and a rash; This spontaneous report was received from a consumer referring to herself, a 70-year-old female patient. The patient's concurrent conditions included depression, hypertension, blood cholesterol increased, lung disorder, arthropathy and drug hypersensitivity (demerol, morphine, versed, penicillin, statins). The patient's concomitant therapies included gabapentin, tramadol hydrochloride, diclofenac, acetaminophen (TYLENOL), duloxetine hydrochloride, hydrochlorothiazide, potassium chloride, montelukast sodium (SINGULAIR), omeprazole and cholecalciferol. Information regarding the patient's medical history and historical drugs was not provided.   The patient reported that on an unknown date in December 2016, she received a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for immunisation (strength, dose, frequency, route of administration, lot number and expiration date were not reported), and on an unknown date in July 2017, she was diagnosed with shingles due to back pain and a rash. Then in July 2020 (reported as "3 years later"), she had a recurrence of shingles. She reported the pain was affecting her every day life. She believed the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) had caused her to develop shingles. The patient reported during her first episode of shingles she spoke with a lawyer in regards to a class action suit for zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), but she was not included in the suit due to the time frame of her diagnosis. She was no longer pursuing legal action. She would like reimbursement for zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  At the time of reporting, the outcome of the event shingles was unknown.
OTHER_MEDS: gabapentin; tramadol hydrochloride; diclofenac; TYLENOL; duloxetine hydrochloride; hydrochlorothiazide; potassium chloride; SINGULAIR; omeprazole; cholecalciferol
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Blood pressure high; Cholesterol high; Depression; Drug hypersensitivity; Lung disorder; Penicillin allergy; Unspecified disorder of knee joint

As a direct and proximate result of the patient's use of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient had and would continue suffered ongoing injuries, including but not limited to: mental and physical pain and suffering; medical care and treatment for these injuries; significant medical and related expenses as a result of these injuries, including but not limited to medical losses and costs include care for hospitalization, physician care, monitoring, treatment, medications, and supplies; diminished capacity for the enjoyment of life; diminished quality of life; increased risk of premature death, aggravation of preexisting conditions and activation of latent conditions; and other losses and damages; and will continue to suffer such losses, and damages in the future. uncontrollable shaking; uncontrollable chills; sore arm; fever; Initial information received on 01-Dec-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a consumer or non-healthcare professional.  This case involves a 65-years-old female patient who experienced uncontrollable shaking (tremor) and chills, sore arm (pain in extremity) and fever (pyrexia), while she received vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE [FLUZONE HIGH-DOSE QUADRIVALENT].   While going through a transplant many years ago, it was found patient have an antibody to Platelets, and he would have a rejection reaction if the donor platelets were not HLA-matched. During the very scary rejection reaction, it started as a chill then mild shaking, then extreme uncontrollable shaking and chills. The doctor would give me a Darvon injection to abate the reaction.    The patient's past vaccination, concomitant medication and family history were not provided.  In 2020 at 14:00, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE (lot number not reported) via an unknown route at an unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination.  In 2020, the patient developed a horrible reaction It was began with shaking (tremor) (at 19:00) and by 20:00 she woke her husband to help her because she was terrified, the shaking had become so bad and became uncontrollable. Staying under a layer of two blankets, she had put on a shirt, a sweatshirt, winter socks, and then slipper socks over those to try to abate the chills. It was not until she added putting on winter gloves that the chills began to subside a bit. But it was the uncontrollable shaking that was the most unnerving. Also had a usual post-immunization reactions of sore arm (pain in extremity) and fever (pyrexia) (unknown latency) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.  Laboratory details were not reported.  It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  Event description: Patient feels shaking and chills similar to that rejection reaction to platelets with the uncontrollable shaking and chills.  The event outcome was unknown for all events.  There will be no information available on the batch number for this case.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Chills; Shaking; Transplant; Transplant rejection
