SYMPTOM_TEXT: I don't know the exact name or manufacturer of the vaccine. It was a routine seasonal flu vaccine. I receive this vaccine every year at this time.  The nurse who gave it to me commented, "Boy, your muscle is really tight".  I experienced nothing out of the ordinary for several days. Then I experienced immense pain between my shoulder and elbow. I was unable to lift my arm because of the pain and intense muscle weakness. I had difficulty sleeping. The pain increased and did not go away. I called the doctor's office and was asked to come in on 10/23/20.  I explained that the pain was directly related to the injection and was in the spot where the shot had been administered. The doctor said it was likely biceps tendonitis and told me to try applying ice for the next couple of weeks. Called the office again on 11/3/20 when there was still no relief. Spoke to the nurse who advised that the doctor suggests a visit to the orthopedic. Nurse suggested applying heat in the meantime. Felt marginal relief with heat for several days and then it returned to constant pain. Called for an appointment on 11/20/20 with an orthopedic, per recommendation.
LAB_DATA: Orthopedic appointment was on 12/7/20 Was given an xray of the humerus - determined to be normal Diagnosis given was - Rotator Cuff Bursitis with adhesive capsulitis  I received a cortisone injection in my shoulder and was given a prescription for physical therapy - twice a week for 4-6 weeks  There is some improvement since the injection - some reduced pain and increased mobility of my left arm. Physical therapy has not started yet.
OTHER_MEDS: Rosuvastatin Calcium 10mg D3 50 mcg (2000 iu) Women's Daily Multivitamin Gummies

SYMPTOM_TEXT: There was a burning pain during vaccine injection dissimilar to any prior intramuscular injections (uncharacteristically painful).  Following the 16:30 vaccine administration, patient's entire left arm and shoulder grew increasingly sore and tight.  By about 20:00 the soreness was throughout the arm.   By 21:30 the pain was significant, and throbbing.  Patient self administered 1.5 mg oxycodone (left over from dental surgery) and 1000mg acetaminophen around midnight (12/2/2020) and took another 1.5 mg oxycodone every 3 hours, alternating 600 mg ibuprofen and 650 mg acetaminophen each time.  Throbbing pain was severe even with arm/shoulder immobilized.  Patient could never get shoulder to sit comfortably.  Every position felt like shoulder was trying to dislocate.  Finally throbbing pain subsided (after 5 or 6 mg oxycodone) and according to his Fitbit, patient first fell asleep at 07:10 on 12/2/2020.  Upon waking, lower arm was sore but mobile, but shoulder mobility was limited to around 20-30 degrees in any direction with much pain.  By afternoon, shoulder had loosened up enough to raise arm over the head (slowly, over 2 minutes).  Immobility presented the next morning.  Upon this writing on 12/11/2020, patient continues to feel joint pain and the feeling of inflammation or possible bursitis in the joint.  Soreness extends to the elbow.  There was soreness and difficulty positioning the arm while sleeping.  Symptoms persist daily.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Flulike symptoms began immediately upon receiving the Flu shot, that lasted several days. A debilitating intractable headache continued for months on a pain scale between 8 - 10 daily. That slowly declined over the course of 8-12 months to a lower level, but still daily activity inhibiting headache at pain levels between 3-5. This eventually turned into Amplified Musculoskeletal Pain Syndrome covering much of his body because of chronic unrelenting headache. Finally, after many doc visits / hospital visits & stays, we began therapies and medications to begin to control/reduce the pain, which have lasted the last 2 years. He is functioning better and pain is reducing to a level 1 daily, but still not completely resolved. This has been over 3 years.
LAB_DATA: Our physician, who's office administered, said he'd never heard of anything like this and had no idea what it could be. He referred us to the hospital and to specialists. After seeking all of these we have slowly been able to find help and work toward getting our sons life back to where he can be a normal kid again, even with daily chronic never-ending pain. He's been DNA / genetic tested, he has the MTHFR gene where he cannot tolerate vaccines.  He's had MRI/x-rays and headache tests/neurological tests and eye exams/photos. Brain and eye are all normal, as well as neurological tests. This chronic headache was unable to be seen on any of the tests. This child was perfectly normal and healthy before the flu shot and immediately after was never the same.
PRIOR_VAX: After years of research, we believe he has seasonal allergies, potential food allergies (to be tested soon) and skin irritations

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 22 year old male with no significant past medical history who presented with 6 days of abdominal pain, nausea, diarrhea, headache, and muscle aches; symptoms were preceded by fever at home several days prior. He was admitted for pain control and intravenous hydration. Upon further questioning, it was revealed that the patient had received immunization for Japanese encephalitis, flu, and anthrax two days prior to symptoms starting. It was suspected that his symptoms were due to recent immunizations, possibly Japanese encephalitis vaccination. While admitted he received comprehensive infectious workup including urine culture, blood culture, COVID testing, respiratory virus panel that were negative. Chest x-ray showed no significant airspace disease but possible small bilateral pleural effusions with recommendation for follow up chest radiograph in 6 weeks to 3 months. Liver enzymes were noted to be elevated on admission, they downtrended, but remained mildly elevated after resolution of abdominal pain. Hepatitis panel negative. Labs also notable for slight anemia possibly due to administration of IV fluids and 3+ blood, 2 RBCs in the urinalysis with no signs of UTI, recommended repeat labs with PCM after discharge. He did not fever during his hospitalization and his presenting symptoms were resolved prior to discharge.   Due to possible vaccine reaction, the The Agency was contacted prior to patient discharge. The nurse practitioner from the agency stated he would contact one of their specialists for further recommendations or workup that should be done as an out-patient. He additionally recommended an allergy/immunology consult as an out-patient.
OTHER_MEDS: OTC B12, B6, vitamin C and post-workout protein powder

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ~3-5 minutes after receiving the vaccination, the patient started to appear to lose consciousness, displayed weakness, and wheezing and shortness of breath. The pharmacist carefully lowered the patient to the ground and had his staff contact 9-1-1 while he administered an Epi-pen injection to the patient's right outer thigh. The patient immediately responded to the injection, was alert and talkative. EMS arrived and took over. Patient left on his own thereafter (~15 mins). Patient was advised to reach out/follow-up with his physician for medical evaluation.

Patient contacted the pharmacy on next day around 10:12 am and stated about one hour after vaccine administered she started experiencing  shills, ache all over the body, fever 102 F lasted only one night, she was not febrile next day on 12/9/2020. on 12/9/2020 she reported that body pain not as bad as before, she had stomach upset on 12/8/2020, no appetite, sick stomach, nausea and vomiting on 12/8/2020, which she feels fine on 12/9/2020, no nausea and vomiting, and she was able to take some Tylenol on 12/9/2020

July 4 , 2020- right-handed weakness with numbness, slurred speak, and had trouble finding words. July 6, 2020 - couldn't move her entire right side of her body and could not speak at all. Hospitalized on July 6, 2020 and determined she had a stroke based on an MRI. Numerous blood tests were taken along with a 2nd MRI with her braces removed.
LAB_DATA: MRI - July 6, 2020 and July 7, 2020 - determined CNS Vasculitis from an undetermined cause.  Brain Biopsy -  July 10, 2020 - 9 AM  - confirmed CNS Vasculitis - large vessel caused a multifocal stroke

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fever, body aches, shivering, headache, tired.

I had extreme pain in my left upper arm and shoulder. I could not move my left arm up and down without experiencing severe pain that lasted for about 10 days. My doctor prescribed Prednisone, and urgent care prescribed Naproxen. I felt extreme pain in most positions that I sat in or when I lay down. I could barely lift my left arm to a resting position on a table or sofa arm without extreme pain that caused me to wince and even brought tears to my eyes at times. I have never had a reaction even remotely similar to this with another vaccine and never expected it to be this painful. I was very concerned that my arm and shoulder might be permanently damaged. I still feel a twinge at times in my left shoulder when I lift something heavy or reach for something up high.

I received healthcare from Pharmacy in the early evening on October 9, 2020 in the form of the following two vaccines:  DRUG: FLUBLOK QUAD 2020-2021 PFS NDC: 49281-0720-10; QTY: 0.5  DRUG: SHINGRIX VIAL KIT NDC: 58160-0823-11; QTY: 1  Firstly, the flu shot was administered in the left shoulder. I've had many a flu shot, and none were this painful. I think the young man pharmacist didn't use the proper length needle, because I had the sensation that the needle went right through the muscle and into the bone. It hurt a lot, so much so that I let out an un-ladylike expletive.  Second was the Shingles shot in the right shoulder. I once again had the sensation that the needle went all the way through my muscle and into the bone. It hurt a lot. Later that same evening, I felt nauseous like I wanted to throw up, and I had such excruciating pain in my right shoulder that I was screaming & writhing in pain and the neighbor's dog could hear me [by barking in acknowledgement]. I applied ice and I was finally able to fall asleep. It was better the next morning. However, to this day (today is 12/14/2020 as I write this), my shoulder is not the same. I am not able to reach for things or use my shoulder in certain ways without experiencing pain and discomfort. I don't think the young man pharmacist followed proper technique in administering the vaccine(s) to me. And I feel sorry for all his prior and subsequent patients, both young and old.  Upon reading articles on the internet about the proper technique for administering shots (in order to help explain the extraordinary pain I've been having in my right shoulder weeks after my shot at Pharmacy on 10/9/2020), I've come to the conclusion that the needle was too long. Also, I don't remember the pharmacist bunching up my muscle first before giving me the shot. I'm not saying that it didn't happen; it's just that I don't remember whether he did or not. In my mind, I'm thinking that he didn't.
LAB_DATA: Does not apply, but I want to know if my vaccines are still valid if, in fact, they were not administered directly into the muscle like they were supposed to. And I want to know what I can do about my should pain, if it can be remedied or if irreversible damage has been done. Thank you.
ALLERGIES: None that I am aware of.

On unknown dates (reported as "shortly after"), the pt was diagnosed with chronic Inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy(CIDP), myopathy, thrombocytopenia, hearing loss (deafness), syncope, and muscle weakness, that resulted in extensive medical treatment (unspecified). It was stated that the symptoms have resulted in serious, progressive, severe, permanent personal and incurable injuries/physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) and that these injuries have resulted in extensive medical treatment and have severely and negatively affected the pt's quality of life, as well as, well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The pt also claimed loss of consortium., loss of services and economic losses (medical expenses; the loss of accumulations). The outcome of the events was not recovered.  The reporter considered all aforementioned events disabling and to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  Upon internal review, the events chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, syncope, deafness and thrombocytopenia to be medically significant.

This case involved a 17 year old male patient who was vaccinated with 0.5ml dose of INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV] via intramuscular route at right arm for prophylactic vaccination (lot number UJ509AA and expiry date 10-May-2021) on 01-Nov-2020 in error instead of the appropriate INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE [FLUZONE QUADRIVALENT] with no adverse event (AE) (product administered to patient of inappropriate age and wrong product administered).   The patient's medical history, past medical treatment, past vaccination, family history and concomitant medication were not provided.  It was a potential medication error due to product administered to patient of inappropriate age and wrong product administered (latency same day). The reporter reported that she went to grab the vaccine the INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE but as both INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE and INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE  were side by side and the 180 and over was not circled and also the trade names of the vaccines namely Flublok and Fluzone were too similar and the boxes were very similar and she was in a hurry and accidentally grabbed the wrong box. postherpetic neuralgia; multiple outbreaks of herpes zoster; This spontaneous report has been received from a lawyer, regarding a case in litigation and refers to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On or about 08-AUG-2013, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot # and expiry date were not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient suffered multiple outbreaks of herpes zoster and post herpetic neuralgia. As a result of these symptoms, the patient was seen and treated by medical providers and was still under their care. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the patient's condition. As a result of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result, the patient suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was considered to be not recovered.  The events of multiple shingles outbreaks and postherpetic neuralgia were considered to be disabling.

Started as a runny nose then progressed to swelling of the nose and eyes. A rash started on the face and then by morning had progressed to a full body itchy rash. We went to the hospital er and they sent us to the pediatric ICU for the night. They ran many test and by the time we were released they told us it was something "viral". There was a slight rash left over. We were referred to an allergist and he said it looked viral from the pictures i showed him. We scheduled for allergy testing but then the pandemic hit.
LAB_DATA: Chest x-ray to rule out valley fever and pneumonia. Blood test with results of elevated white blood cells. IV. Central line which was used for 30 minutes until her arm started swelling.  The test were ran on November 16th-17th.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: (I completed a form before this one with a previous reaction to the flu shot in 2019) The reaction this time around was allergy like symptoms, swelling and red rash around the face that spread within a few hours to the whole body. The rash was very hot and itchy and her temperature got to 101 at home. This is a head to bottom of feet rash that covers her whole body. (we have pictures from both occasions). The reaction started 10 days after the vaccine and we took her in to the er on the 24th of October. We tried to control it with the medications we were sent home with from the last visit but it was not working. She was tested for Covid and other viral infections. IV. She was sent to the hospital for the night. Neither time was anaphylactic. The first time they used an epi pen (I forgot to mention) that worked in making her comfortable for 45 min but then it came back worse. She had diarrhea and vomiting both times.
LAB_DATA: She tested positive for a common cold on october 24th. Her white blood cells were elevated.
PRIOR_VAX: Age 4, flu shot, 11/15/2019, same brand and dosage of this one

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reports that she received influenza and pneumococcal vaccine around 9 am on 12/1/2020 and approximately one hour later, started developing pain in the left arm where the 2 vaccines had been given.  She presented to urgent care on 12/2/2020 with pain 10/10 , "patchy erythematous plaque-like rash over the lateral mid to distal deltoid area of the left arm. . No central clearing or central pallor. No papules, vesicles, or other skin lesion changes. Allodynia tenderness palpation." per provider  She was to continue to take acetaminophen and ibuprofen and start cetirizine.  Later on 12/2/2020, she presented to the emergency room with a fever Temperature maximum of 102, dysuria, tachycardia and leukocytosis. COVID-19 and influenza tests were negative. Per provider, the urinalysis was negative for infection and she was negative for sepsis and meningitis. At that time, the provider reported that there was some firmness and erythema on her left upper arm consistent with cellulitis. She was given fluids, pain medications and cephalexin. On 12/7/2020, she presented with increased edema since 12/2/2020.  She had taken 5 days of cephalexin and she chose to continue to take the cephalexin versus changing to another antibiotic at that time. On 12/10/2020, significant improvement noted by provider, with only tenderness to the area. Patient to continue to take cephalexin.
LAB_DATA: 22.3 K/uL WBC on 12/4/2020 Absolute neutrophils 18.8 Ku/uL on 12/4/2020
CUR_ILL: right side scapular pain from work injury

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On approximately October 12, after receiving the Gardasil 9 vaccine on September 30, I noticed that my "sore" left arm was not just sore but had a nodule in the tissue. I measured the nodule, and it was about 2 cm in diameter. I applied heat and massaged it, but it did not help. I messaged my provider's office on October 18 to ask if this was abnormal and if I should do anything else. My provider replied that I should continue to apply heat and that this was normal. I did apply heat as often as possible, and I even slept with heat for several hours at a time. This did not seem to speed up the resolution of the nodule. The nodule increased in size to 3 cm and swelled up to a round knot. I would say that it was 3 cm diameter by the end of October and increasingly sore and heavy. It gradually decreased in size in the latter half of November. Today I have no nodule but my left arm is still slightly sore. I still do not feel that I could receive another vaccine in the left arm without anxiety because of the soreness.
OTHER_MEDS: Trokendi Emgality Botox migraine Allegra Nasacort Dexilant naratriptan baclofen trazodone Vision Pro EPA/DHA/GLA vitamin d vitamin B12 magnesium oxide lorazepam

In January 2020, the patient experienced ear infection and bronchitis. In July 2020, the patient experienced shingles. Patient reported her doctor prescribed an antiviral medication for the shingles. The patient reported she had bronchitis and an ear infection in January 2020 and these have resolved. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On September 16, 2019 I took my son, Patient to his 15 month check up. He received a DTaP shot at about 11:30am, we got home maybe 20-30 minutes later where I stood him in our living room and got settled. At about 12:00pm he started crying inconsolably, but wouldn?t move.  I said, ?come here,? but he just stood there, cries turning to screams. I grab his hand to get him to walk closer, but he falls over and does not get up.  I pick him up, trying to calm him, but he?s still crying uncontrollably.  I try to stand him in my lap, but he feels limp. I check everything on him, making sure he?s okay, seeing what I can do to help, nothing helps.  I have no clue what?s going on or how to help, so I call the doctors office - I can only hear some of what they are saying, but I try to tell the nurse what?s going on while he cries in the background, the nurse told me that soreness is to be expected and to give some Tylenol.  We?ve had shots before, but never any of this. Never crying like this, never going limp like this.  I finally calm him down and get him to sleep long enough for my husband to come home.  After weeks/months of research, talking to a family friend who had knowledge in this area, and a few nurse friends, I was able to discover that this was a hypotonic hypersensitive episode.   That afternoon and the following few days of that week, it?s as if Patient was re-learning how to walk. He was 15 months and had started walking at 11 months, so this was not a difficult task for him, but he was very clumsy, would stumble and fall several times a day. My husband and I both made comments to each other about him being very clumsy.  Patient also had/has a speech regression/delay which I am confident came after this. I only say this because I spent every day with him before and after and watched the regression and these are the things that I witnessed.  - Patient had been saying: Mama, Dada, Nose, Hair, had been practicing feeding himself, and when asked would point to a body part.  - 09/14/2019 he said ?sit down? his first 2 word sentence ever, (I was so proud, I documented it!) After his shot, he did not say the above words again until just a few months ago after months of speech therapy.  When I asked if he wanted to hold a utensil to help feed himself, he would act as if he were throwing a tantrum.  When his toys (that he has played with for months) would make a noise, he would flinch, when prior to the shot, he never did this.  He did not point to his body parts again for months as well, until speech therapy and months of me working with him again.   A few treatments that have helped are, of course, speech therapy (he began this in maybe February) and glutathione cream.  His doctor now has been amazing and very supportive and has said that he?s improved so much.
HISTORY: Eczema, sensitive skin Idiopathic Urticaria (end of April 2019 - early May 2019 for about a week)

They got a little bigger and a little more red but i figured shes a kid and was scooting around on the ground so I didnt think much of it put some lotion on. December 13th come and she woke up and had those little spots down on her ankles and im like geeze maybe we have bugs in the house. So I checked everybody and couldnt find anybody else who has any little bumps. We went to my moms which is about 45 mins away spent the day with her and she just keeps getting more spots but only on her legs. Then im like well maybe she has the chicken pox! My mom looks at them and they just started growing right before our eyes!   So I go to head home and in that 45 min window they grew about 4X the original size and are now completely covering her legs and butt. I call my nurse friend and shes like maybe its Hives give her some benadryl and see what they look like in the morning so i do that. In the morning they were a dark deep redish purple almost like a bruise so i called the clinic to get her in. They ask a bunch of questions and have her pee in a hat and come back tell me that its something called HSP.   Dr didn't really explain much on what causes it he just said that it can be caused by a few things. So i check the CDC for it and one of the things listed for a cause is the chicken pox. She hasn't been sick hasn't been around anybody who has been sick we have not changed her diet etc so i fell like its an adverse reaction to the shot.   Once he explained to me some of the symptoms I feel like she was showing sooner then December 9th because shes been complaining about her legs and her hands hurting since the first week of December and he said joint pain is a side effect of HSP.   He prescribed a steroid to help keep it out of the kidney and told us to keep an eye out for bloody urine and bloody stool.   We are currently home and she still has her big purple rash on the bottom half of her body.
LAB_DATA: Urine Test--- All he said was the kidneys are fine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: S: Patient presents for ER f/u of immunization reaction concerns. Yesterday, she had an immz. only visit at facility and received her 1st dose of Gardasil HPV in right arm at 3:54 pm and 1st dose of Menveo Meningococcal ACYW in right arm at 3:55 pm. Mother reports she was in her usual state of health yesterday and felt fine that evening laughing and participating in family activities, then around 9 pm her eyes suddenly seemed puffy and she got a confused look on her face, saying she was dizzy. She additionally developed clamminess/chills without fever, nausea without vomiting and a headache which is throbbing over her whole head without vision or hearing changes. Mother called the after hours line and was directed to take patient to ER, where they waited for "hours" with patient evaluated by provider at 3:54 am (per record note) with limited w/u including rapid strep, which was negative, and impression that symptoms were likely due to vaccinations.  Mother reports that today, Patient is about the same with all symptoms above still present. Patient reports she has a stuffy nose and non-phlegmy cough, which mother has not noticed. She denies neck stiffness, difficulty swallowing, ear or throat pain, rashes or diarrhea. She adds that she feels achy btu can move all extremities without difficulty. Right arm is sore at injection site with no known swelling. Patient has a decreased appetite today though has tolerated water and fruit and has voided a couple of times. She took ibuprofen yesterday and tylenol today without much improvement. There is no prior history of immunizations or known drug allergies.  O: Patient ambulatory, conversational, laughing at times. Exam significant for mild eyelid swelling and mild pharyngeal inflammation. Additional systems examined (ears, nose, mouth, neck, skin, lungs, heart, abdomen, neurological) all WNL. A: Possible immunization reaction versus acute infection. P: Detailed discussion with mother regarding possible immunization reaction to either HPV or Menveo versus infection, given acute onset. Convoluted history from mother regarding possible meningitis last year with similar symptoms, with records requested to review more thoroughly, however advised mother that at this time, patient does not have any signs of meningitis and that meningitis immunization does not cause meningitis infection. Rapid flu negative and COVID test ordered; as patient overall well appearing today will defer additional w/u unless symptoms worsen or do not improve as expected over the next 5-7 days. Zofran prescribed for nausea with administration discussed, recommend offering Pediasure and OTC ibuprofen/Tylenol PRN discomfort. Go to ER if syncope, neck stiffness, no voids for 8 hours, changes in speech/coordination, severe worsening of headache or any other concerns. Mother verbalizes understanding. Will report presentation to VAERS.
LAB_DATA: 12/2015: Rapid strep and rapid influenza A/B negative.

I am a immunization nurse at this location.  I gave 2 of the first 4 Covid vaccinations given at our location.  Then I received dose # 5.  It was easy.  I did a couple of things and then returned to my desk.  As I sat down, my arm started feeling very heavy.  I was unable to send a text.  I told staff that I was feeling funny and that I was going to the other room to lay down.  Staff followed me and took my Pulse 100 and BP 164/ 82 (high for me!)  .  I felt shaky, but my hands were not shaking.  Put a wet cloth on my head and laid there a few minutes, telling staff stories and laughing at my BP.  When I sat up, my BP was 126/74 and pulse was 80.  I stood up for a minute or two, then my legs got heavy and I sat down for a few more minutes.  I went to the bathroom and came back to my desk, but was weak and tired.  I ate and drank some fluids.  Because it was snowing  and I live 25 miles away, I accepted a ride home from a co-worker.  I walked across the parking lot without problems and talked all the way home.  At home, I was tired, but had a sandwich and talked on the phone.  I would still describe myself as tired, but functioning.

ALLERGIES: Allergies: Morphine Spinal and Lumigan (Bimatoprost oph. sol.)

Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine EUA  Developed chills, nausea and vomiting beginning at 2 AM the night after receiving the vaccine. Potential fever as well (I don't have a thermometer to check). Symptoms have lasted over 3 hours thus far, still continuing.

By 8PM I was feeling extremely tired, went to bed. Woke up at 11:30PM with a fever was cold and shivering, Woke up again at 1:30AM and my mouth was completely dry and my right hand was cramped and could not move. These all my Sjogren's symptoms but more severe than I had ever felt them before. At 4:30AM my fever was 99.3 and I still had all the aforementioned symptoms. I was extremely tired and felt nauseous. By 8AM I had stomach cramping followed by diarrhea. My stomach was too upset to eat at all the entire day of the 14th. I had off and on stomach pains with diarrhea. I was very tired and could not stay awake for very long. My temperature went back down to my normal 97.2 by 10 AM. My right hand is still very hard to move and painful today on the 16TH. My stomach still feels queasy. I have not had a fever again, but still feel horrible. I have not gone to my primary doctor because there is nothing he can do to help.
LAB_DATA: did not go to the doctor
OTHER_MEDS: Losartan 50mg Baby Aspirin Flonase 50mg red rice yeast pill 600mg garlic oil 1000mg

twinges (of pain) in his left thigh; soreness at the injection site (left shoulder).; nerve pain perhaps shingles-type nerve pain; asked if the shot was given intramuscularly  / is not sure because but the person administering the shot did pinch his skin up; he couldn't get comfortable while sleeping; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in extremity in a 76-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 3rd December 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 3rd December 2020, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain in extremity, injection site pain, nerve pain and intramuscular formulation administered by other route. In December 2020, the patient experienced discomfort. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in extremity, injection site pain and discomfort were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the nerve pain and intramuscular formulation administered by other route were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in extremity, nerve pain, discomfort and intramuscular formulation administered by other route to be related to Shingrix. The reporter considered the injection site pain to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were received as follows: The patient received Shingrix around 2:00 or 2:30 pm in the left deltoid. The customer care asked, if the shot was given intramuscularly and the patient said he thinks so but was not sure because but the person administering the shot did pinch his skin up and he states that he did not recall his skin being pinched up for Shingrix dose 1. He indicated that he did not know if pinching the skin up would have affected the ability of the needle to reach the muscle. When asked the patient if the injection was done on the back of the arm and he said no.   The patient was experiencing soreness at the injection site (left shoulder). This had not resolved. He reported that yesterday by evening he experienced twinges (of pain) in his left thigh. He was not sure if it was nerve pain perhaps shingles-type nerve pain. The pain was on the inside of the left thigh, high up, sharp and local. He said the pain kept him up for a couple hours last night (in the middle of the night) because he couldn't get comfortable while sleeping. He said the pain comes and goes and he did not injure himself or do anything out of the ordinary. He said the pain comes in waves. The pain was a little better this morning  but he did have a sharp leg/thigh pain right before calling. The patient was calling because he wanted to see if he should call his doctor. He was concerned that maybe the pain could be something serious like a blood clot. He stated he was almost sure this the thigh pain wa related to the Shingrix shot because it started a few hours after getting the shot. The reporter consented to follow up.

Patient had clinically recovered from hypotension and syncope so she was scheduled for discharge. In accordance with hospital policy, patient was offered an influenza vaccine prior to discharge. Approximately 10-15 minutes after receiving the vaccine, patient was being assisted to the bathroom when she lost consciousness, fell backwards, hit her head on the wall, and fell to the floor. The patient became pulseless with agonal breathing. CPR was initiated, an IV was reinserted, and a non-rebreather w/ surgical mask was placed. ROSC was achieved after 20-25 minutes. During the code, the patient received epinephrine x 4, cardioversion x 4, and bicarb x 2. She was intubated and transferred to the ICU where she underwent targeted temperature management. She ultimately sustained end organ damage requiring her to become dialysis dependent. Hospital course was further complicated by a massive GI bleed and infection. Patient ultimately died on 11/12/2020
OTHER_MEDS: Apixaban, digoxin, lactated ringers, Risaquad, metoprolol succinate
HISTORY: Atrial fibrillation, chronic systolic heart failure,

Got the PNEUMOVAX 23 shot on 11/18/2020 - I began having reaction 11/21.  I had high fevers up to 103.8 for over a week. Since symptoms were similar, I got a COVID test on 11/21 which was negative. 11/24 I developed hives over my whole body, mouth, lips, torso, thighs, arms, which lasted 3 weeks. The doctor prescribed Hydroxyzine which didn't help much. On 11/25 - the Dr. prescribed Prednisone 20mg to help with the hives and calm it down. On 11/28 developed wheezing, shortness of breath and on 11/30 - was analyzed for heart and lungs issues by paramedics. On 12/8 - GP - Dr. diagnosed me with possible reactive airway dysfunction and prescribed an inhaler.   I've found that then inhaler alone does not do the trick.  Since the word reactive is in the diagnosis, I figured I'd try an antihistamine.  I tried Benadryl but it is not as long lasting.  On Sunday, I tried taking  a Benadryl over night and then didn't take a Zyrtec first thing to see how it went. I did not go out to the barn or do any big activities.  I ended up having breathing problems.     I'm 67 and have never had a reaction like this in my life. I am still having breathing problems as of today 12/16. I had a pneumonia shot 10 years ago and had no reaction. I had the flu shot -by Sanofi Pasteur on October 28th  and had the expected  mild reaction - sore arm, felt a little crummy part of one day.  No big deal.  I went about my activities.  Previous to this, I have never used an inhaler in my life. I'm not a smoker. I've started taking Zyrtec 1x per day in the morning  to help with the reactive lung issues. This seems to work the best at this time.  If I don't take it, I start having breathing issues.    I am allergic to penicillin, sulfa drugs, and cephalosporins.   I am a professional photographer, do quite a bit of walking for my profession.   I also have horses, ride 2-3 times per week & do daily chores with the horses. I also care for my grandson part time.  I'm an active person. This has left me with much lower energy and breathing problems which I've never experienced in my life!  I don't know if this is permanent, but I sure hope not!  It has prevented me from caring for my grandson at times, has curtailed my riding and horse care activities, and has curtailed my ability to hike and walk for my photographic business.  I'm concerned about my reaction to the pneumonia vaccine and the ability to take a COVID-19 vaccine when it becomes available.
LAB_DATA: Covid Test - 11/21 since the symptoms were similar.  The results were NEGATIVE. 11/30 - Visit to fire station for shortness of breath where they did an EKG, took my blood pressure, and took a pulse ox reading all which were in the normal range.
OTHER_MEDS: Levothyroxine - 137 mcg   Vitamins:  B12, Multi Vitamin, Vit D, Zinc, tumeric, baby aspirin, joint supplement

The patient's concurrent conditions included pressure headaches from storms, melanoma (found in December 2003), thyroid disorder and diabetes. Concomitant therapies included levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID), colesevelam hydrochloride and metformin hydrochloride. She was divorced. The patient was allergic to pollen from every tree except cottonwood, to every pain medication in the world (codeine, morphine, ibuprofen, naproxen (reported as "naproysyn"), acetaminophen, sulindac (CLINORIL), tramadol, anaphylaxis to opioids; she was able take aspirin - she limited herself to 6 tablets per year), also allergic to fluoride, synthetic tetanus, band aid adhesive and sulfa drugs, to night shade family (tomatoes, eggplant, potatoes and bell peppers; bell pepper and egg plant caused anaphylaxis to her; she could walk into the produce department and the oil got in the air from a bell pepper and she would start having a reaction), tobacco, ants, bees and wasps and insect bites (she got anaphylaxis if she got stung by ants, bees, wasp and insect bites), carbon paper, cleaning chemicals, dust, eucalyptus (the scent of it in the air caused her eyes to start swelling; she has not been able to wear make up), mold, pesticides, smoke, synthetic fabrics (like polyester) and synthetic perfumes, tree sap (the saps from Evergreen and tropical varieties of plants, like palm trees, caused rashing). She could eat eggs and was not allergic to eggs. She could eat tree nuts like pecans and walnuts, yet she was allergic to the pollen from the tree. On an unknown date in September 1967 (reported as in the fall of 1967), she received her first flu vaccine. She had the flu vaccine again the next year in 1968. She had a big goose egg, rashing, and problems breathing. She had a reaction again. She has never had another flu vaccine and has not had the flu either. On an unknown date in approximately 2012 (8 years ago, also reported as the last time), she had an opioid, which was from a dentist. He said she would not be allergic to it. She believed him and took it. In less than 15 minutes, she was projectile vomiting into the toilet. Those are some of her symptoms.   On an unknown date in approximately 2013 (reported as "when she turned 65 years"), the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (manufacturer unknown) (strength, dose, route of administration, lot number and expiry date were not reported) for prophylaxis.  On an unknown date, the patient experienced a site reaction to the vaccine. Additionally, where the shot was given, the site was a little red. She stated it was not a big reaction. On an unknown date in October 2019, the patient was vaccinated with the second dose of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23).  On an unspecified date, the patient experienced forgetting words that she did not use very often. The pharmacist made a lot of calls (not further clarified) and told them that she had a reaction to pneumococcal 13v conj vaccine (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13) and they did not think she would have a reaction to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23). Additionally, the patient experienced a site reaction, where it got red and warm. It did not swell above the skin. Since an unknown date in approximately 2019 (reported as last year), the patient started to loose her heigh. The entire time she was in high school and she was 5 foot 7 inches. This past year she was down to 5 foot 4.5 inches. Last year, caller was down to 5 foot 5.5 inches and this year, she was 5 foot 4.5 inches. She has lost two and a half inches. On an unknown date, the patient experienced cataract. On 09-JUN-2020, she had cataract surgery on her right eye and on 14-JUL-2020, she had cataract surgery on her left arm performed. She had far vision implants put in both eyes. The outcome of the events was not reported.  The event of vaccination site reaction was considered to be related to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23). Guillain Barre; This spontaneous case was received on 22-Sep-2020 from other non-health professional (consumer) via Communications (reference number: SEQW20-02122) and concerned a 69-year-old male patient (the patient's age was also reported as 66 years).   The patient had no medical history before receiving the vaccine. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. Reportedly, before vaccination, the patient was playing tennis and was very active, he was healthy, and he barely even had the flu.   On 23-Sep-2012, the patient was vaccinated with Fluvirin vaccine, 5 ml multi dose vial (MDV), (inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported) for flu prophylaxis. The batch number was not reported.  On an unknown date, shortly after receiving Fluvirin, the patient started not feeling well. He could barely walk and since then he became "a couch potato" (as reported).  On an unspecified date in Oct-2012, about a month later after receiving Fluvirin vaccine, the patient's balance was off, and he stated that fluid was taken out of his spine and was diagnosed with Guillain Barre syndrome.  On an unknown date, the patient was hospitalized due diagnosis of Guillain Barre syndrome.   On unspecified dates, for the next 7-8 years after receiving Fluvirin vaccine, the patient was in and out of the hospitals with multiple problems. The patient had a brain scan that revealed whiteness.   At the time of initial reporting on 22-Sep-2020, the patient had not recovered from the event and he had to walk with a walker.  The reporter considered the event of 'Guillain Barre syndrome' to be related to Fluvirin. The reporter spent the last eight years researching the cause of the disease and found that it could have been caused by the flu vaccine he had received.   This case is linked to 202005002 (the same reporter).   The event of 'Guillain Barre syndrome' was considered to be serious due to hospitalization and medical significance by a Physician within Seqirus' Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  Additional information received on 06-Oct-2020 from other non-health professional (consumer): Reporter's causality was provided. Narrative was amended accordingly.  Additional information received on 04-Nov-2020 from other non-health professional (consumer) via Communications (reference number: SEQW20-04768): Correspondence contact added. Date of vaccination was provided, and indication verbatim was amended from 'influenza prophylaxis' to 'flu prophylaxis'. Hospitalization added as seriousness criterion for the event. The narrative was amended accordingly.   Company comment: A 69-year-old male patient was vaccinated with Fluvirin vaccine. About a month later after receiving Fluvirin vaccine, the patient's balance was off, and he stated that fluid was taken out of his spine and was diagnosed with Guillain Barre syndrome. Chronology is plausible. More information regarding diagnostic findings, medical history and concomitant medications is needed. Reportedly, before vaccination, the patient was playing tennis and was very active. Based on provided information, causality is assessed as possibly related. Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Preterm birth at 32.6 weeks of gestation; Low birth weight of 1984 g; This observational study case, initially received on 07-Dec-2020 from other health professional and concerned a female neonate subject, whose mother was 31-year-old, pregnant subject of body weight 146 lbs, height 63 inches and body mass index (BMI): 25.9,  enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.   The neonate's mother's concurrent conditions included increased BMI. The mother's concomitant medications included Niferex (polysaccharide-iron complex) and Prenatal vitamins (minerals not specified (nos), vitamins nos) both used for pregnancy.  The mother's obstetrical history included no previous pregnancies. The neonate's mother had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). Also, the neonate's mother had no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The neonate's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was reported as 07-Apr-2020. The mother's estimated delivery date (EDD) was not reported and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was 12-Jan-2021 . The type of pregnancy was singleton. The neonate's father was 31-year-old.  On 08-Jun-2020, the ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 30-Jun-2020, first trimester screen revealed increased risk for Down's syndrome and no MCM. Also, ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 12-Aug-2020, ultrasound revealed no MCM.  On 27-Oct-2020, at approximately 29 weeks of gestation (calculated per LMP), the neonate's mother was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine, dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100265371.  On 11-Nov-2020, 15 days after receiving Afluria QIV, the neonate's mother developed premature rupture of membranes.  At gestational age of 32.6 weeks (as reported), the mother delivered a preterm live birth, female neonate vaginally. The neonate birth weight was 1984 grams, head circumference 30 cm and length 44.5 cm. Appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). No date for APGAR score at 10 minutes was provided. No MCM was identified at birth.  On the same day, the mother recovered from prolonged premature rupture of membranes.  The outcome for the events 'premature baby 26 to 32 weeks' and 'low birth weight baby' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  The events 'premature baby 26 to 32 weeks' and 'low birth weight baby' were considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked to the case 202007590, the corresponding mother case.  Company comment: A female neonate subject, whose mother was 31-year-old pregnant subject, experienced premature baby and low birth weight baby 15 days after administration of Afluria QIV to the subject's mother. Causality is assessed as unrelated to vaccine due to unsuggestive chronology and biological implausibility and more likely related to the increased BMI of the subject's mother. Increased BMI most likely resulted in premature rupture of membranes and premature delivery/ low birth weight baby. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: A female neonate subject, whose mother was 31-year-old pregnant subject, experienced premature baby and low birth weight baby 15 days after administration of Afluria QIV to the subject's mother. Causality is assessed as unrelated to vaccine due to unsuggestive chronology and biological implausibility and more likely related to the increased BMI of the subject's mother. Increased BMI most likely resulted in premature rupture of membranes and premature delivery/ low birth weight baby. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company conventions.

Pt had been escorted from observation area to emergency area with PA with c/o tightness in throat.  On my arrival, pt was eupneic, p/w/d, ambulatory, NAD. Patient received her vaccination at approximately 1021.  Patient reports symptoms onset at approximately 1038 with tightness of the throat and difficulty swolowing.  She described it as a swelling of the throat sensation.  She states she had a sensation moving from her head to her toes as in a "wave ".     Patient denied shortness of breath, chest pain denies nausea.  Patient denies hives or rashes or pruitis.     Patient was assessed and  moved to the emergency area.   Her symptoms continued with some improvement.  At this point time 25 mg of Benadryl was administered orally. Approximately 10 to 15 minutes after administration the patient developed numbness tingling around the upper lip, the right upper extremity.  She denied shortness of breath or chest pain.  She denied increasing severity of the throat sensations.   Pertinent past medical history: Reactions bee stings currently carries EpiPen.    She is not had any previous reactions to vaccinations.      Allergic reaction.   The patient symptoms seem to continue with the numbness tingling around the lips after administration of the Benadryl.  Hand tingling of the right upper extremity also continued although it was decreasing.   Her symptoms of the tightness of the throat remain the same. She did not develop shortness or breath or chest tightness or pain.    At this time I feel be prudent to evacuate the patient to higher level care.   Patient was evacuated at 11:16 by ambulance service.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received Tdap shot (unsure whether Adacel or Boostrix at time of filing report) on 12/04/2020 during appointment at 3:00 PM.  Tdap was indicated because I was 28 weeks pregnant at the time of the appointment.  My estimated due date is 02/24/2021 and I am currently 30 weeks pregnant at the time of this report.  When I got the shot, it didn't hurt any more than usual for any other vaccine that I have received.  Towards the evening, I started getting soreness in my arm.  By the morning of 12/05/2020, I could not move my arm very much and it was extremely sore.  I assumed it was just a normal reaction to the shot.  It seemed to get a little better over the next few days, but the pain never actually went away.  It just dulled.  On 12/12/2020, I began to become concerned because it had been a week since receiving the shot and I still was experiencing pain.  I noticed the pain was worse when I slept at night and my range of motion was becoming worse.  I tried taking Tylenol and icing the area, but the pain was only temporarily dulled.  I woke up throughout the early morning of 12/15/2020 with excruciating pain in my left shoulder and arm.  I called out of work and went to a doctor's office to be evaluated.  I was diagnosed with subacromial bursitis of the left shoulder.  Currently, I am wearing a sling to get through the work day and cannot move my arm much because it is too painful.  It is hard to function occupationally and I am having a hard time doing simple tasks, such as putting my clothes on and going to the bathroom.  I was told it would probably take weeks to heal and was referred to physical therapy in the meantime.  I am currently not sure if this will result in permanent damage or disability.  I am currently unable to perform all of my job duties and am limited to light desk work in the meantime until this injury has healed.
LAB_DATA: Was evaluated on 12/15/2020 at healthcare clinic and diagnosed with subacromial bursitis of the left shoulder.  No additional medical tests or lab work was performed.
OTHER_MEDS: Loratadine 10 mg daily Flonase nasal spray - 2 sprays in each nostril daily Sertraline 50 mg daily Doxylamine 25 mg at bedtime Prenatal vitamin daily

The Patient was given her vaccine on October 27th in the afternoon. The shot itself was not painful.  At first, The Patient arm was sore so I gave her Tylenol. Later that evening she complained of her hand swelling so I gave her Advil. Her hand had gotten so swollen that she could not bend her fingers. The next day we had a virtual visit with the physician who suggested The Patient start taking Benadryl. I gave her Benadryl throughout the day but it was not helping with the swelling. On Friday, we went into the doctor's office and they prescribed a steroid to take. She took it, along with Benadryl, for 7 days and the swelling did not improve. On November 6, we saw an allergist, Dr. who did not believe it was an allergy. She told The Patient to keep her arm as elevated as possible to help bring down the swelling. The swelling came down significantly within 24 hours; however, her hand was still tender and not able to bend her fingers. Over the next week, I could see a drainage under the skin (no visible fluid) and after about another week her  hand looked normal. Now, in early-mid December her hand is much improved - about 95% functional (still a bit tender if she applies pressure)
LAB_DATA: No test but was evaluated in person by an allergist and then virtually by a neurologist, Dr.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Following the first shot in the series of the Gardasil vaccine on 10/20/2006, within a week, I broke out in hives on my back that were unexplainable.  I went to the doctor, they told me to take Benadryl and apply Cortisone cream.  There were no other causes for the hives such as clothing, soap, detergent, etc.  The hives would come back up on different parts of my body for the following weeks. I received my second shot in the series on 1/19/2007, the hives have gotten worse and continue to stay longer and cover more of my body.  I then received the final dose on 5/7/2007.  From this point, I have seen a dermatologist, several allergists, an infectious disease specialist regarding why I am having systemic hives that are not controlled by allergy medications.  I underwent many tests and procedures including a biopsy of my skin hive, and a test that came back as markers for Lupus were present.    I was taking several allergy medications, Predisone steroids long term, and  Zantac for the awful heartburn and indigestion that felt like I was having a heart attack- I also have dental enamel damage from those years of intense acid indigestion. I was prescribed an epipen because my throat and tongue would swell up so bad.  My face would swell so much that I couldn't see due to my eyes being swollen shut.  I could not walk because the hives covered the bottoms of my feet.  I spent the last part of my high school career and much of the first part of my college life miserable and covered in hives.  I also gained 40-50 pounds due to the steroids I had to take daily.

Anaphylaxis reaction/severe allergic reaction; arm is still sore from the vaccine; This spontaneous report was received from a consumer refers to a 6-year-old male patient. The patient had no concomitant medications. The patient's pertinent medical history included immunocompromised. The patient was recently tested positive for celiac.  On 10-DEC-2020, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (lot# reported as F023835 was evaluated and changed to the valid lot # S023835, expiration date not reported, upon internal validation established as 18-MAY-2021; strength, dose and route were not reported) in the arm for prophylaxis.       On the same day within 2 minutes after receiving the vaccine, the patient had an anaphylaxis reaction. While at the doctor's office, the patient started coughing and clearing his throat a lot. The patient had a mask on, was coughing more with whole face swelling and broke out in a rash when got outside of the doctor's office. The patient had "snot coming from nose" and was wheezing and collapsed. The consumer took the patient back inside the doctor's office and reported one of the doctor's got an epinephrine hydrochloride (EPIPEN) and before administering the epinephrine hydrochloride (EPIPEN), the patient woke up and reported they did not need to use the epinephrine hydrochloride (EPIPEN). The reaction was short lived and the patient reacted well to the diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL). After the patient woke up from the anaphylaxis reaction, they were very confused and off in space. The patient was having "face ticks" that were "very strange". The patient was not hospitalized, and his arm was still sore from the vaccine. By giving the patient diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL) throughout the night to be sure the patient would not have another reaction. The patient was doing much better next day and recovered from the severe allergic reaction. The outcome of sore arm was not reported. The reporter considered sore arm to be related to Pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23). The causality assessment between other events and Pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was not reported.  Upon internal review, anaphylaxis reaction was determined to be medically significant.

a subsequent non-traumatic fall; Paresthesias/tingling and electrical shock sensations; numbness on the dorsal region of her right lower extremity; difficulty lifting both legs; bilateral proximal lower extremity weakness; initially started with inability to ascend stairs; difficulty with standing; Guillain-Barre syndrome; acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (GBS); endorse microvascular ischemic disease involving the white matter; nondisplaced spiral fracture; Inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion; bilateral absent Patellar and Achilles tendon reflexes; degenerative antegrade spondylolisthesis deformity at L5-S1; neuropathic pain in bilateral lower extremities; burning sensation; difficulties with swallowing; esophageal dysmotility; hyponatremic; Blood pressure fluctuation; unfortunately feels; Weakness/muscular strength continued to decline; large ankle joint effusion; lower extremity pain; Dysautonomia; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of guillain barre syndrome in a 76-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included hyperlipidemia, asthma, macular degeneration, pancreatitis (two previous episodes of unknown origin) and upper respiratory tract infection (mild, ten weeks prior to admission).   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, 8 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced guillain barre syndrome (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), demyelinating polyneuropathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant), weakness in extremity (serious criteria hospitalization), gait disturbance (serious criteria hospitalization), difficulty in standing (serious criteria hospitalization), cerebral small vessel ischemic disease (serious criteria GSK medically significant), fall (serious criteria hospitalization), paresthesia (serious criteria hospitalization), numbness of lower extremities (serious criteria hospitalization), movement disorder (serious criteria hospitalization), femur fracture (serious criteria GSK medically significant), absent ankle jerk, spondylolisthesis, neuropathic pain, burning sensation, swallowing difficult, dyskinesia of esophagus, hyponatremia, blood pressure fluctuation, feeling sad, weakness, joint effusion, pain of lower extremities, inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and dysautonomia. The patient was treated with immunoglobulins nos (Immunoglobulin), gabapentin and amitriptyline. On an unknown date, the outcome of the guillain barre syndrome, demyelinating polyneuropathy, weakness in extremity, gait disturbance, difficulty in standing, cerebral small vessel ischemic disease, fall, paresthesia, numbness of lower extremities, movement disorder, absent ankle jerk, spondylolisthesis, neuropathic pain, burning sensation, swallowing difficult, dyskinesia of esophagus, hyponatremia, blood pressure fluctuation, feeling sad, weakness, joint effusion, pain of lower extremities and inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the femur fracture and dysautonomia were unknown.   The reporter considered the guillain barre syndrome, demyelinating polyneuropathy, weakness in extremity, gait disturbance, difficulty in standing, cerebral small vessel ischemic disease, fall, paresthesia, numbness of lower extremities, movement disorder, absent ankle jerk, spondylolisthesis, neuropathic pain, burning sensation, swallowing difficult, dyskinesia of esophagus, hyponatremia, weakness, pain of lower extremities,blood pressure fluctuation, feeling sad, joint effusion, inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion and dysautonomia to be related to Shingrix. It was unknown if the reporter considered the femur fracture to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS) in a 76-year-old female patient, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis. The patient had past medical history of hyperlipidemia, asthma, macular degeneration, and two previous episodes of pancreatitis of unknown origin. The patient denied recent camping, hiking, insect bites, and prior neuropathy/myopathy. However, the patient did report a mild upper respiratory tract infection ten weeks prior to admission. No information on patient's family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, 10 (ten) days before hospitalization, the patient received Shingrix (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided but it could be 75 years or 76 years. [The Patient stated that she had received the new Shingrix (Recombinant Zoster) vaccine ten days before hospitalization]. On an unspecified date, 10 days after vaccination, the patient presented with a two-day history of bilateral proximal lower extremity weakness. The patient reported that the patient had progressive weakness that initially started with inability to ascend stairs. This progressed to difficulty with standing and a subsequent non-traumatic fall. These described symptoms deviated significantly from her baseline. The Patient's baseline consisted of independence with mobility and activities of daily living. The patient did not require any assistive devices. On presentation, the patient was afebrile (98.4 degree Fahrenheit), had a normal respiratory rate (17 breaths/minute), had an oxygen saturation of 98% on room air, and was normotensive (136/76 mmHg). The patient reported paresthesias and numbness on the dorsal region of her right lower extremity and difficulty lifting both legs. On examination, the patient was alert and oriented, cranial nerves II-XII were intact, there was 5/5 bilateral upper extremity strength, and 5/5 bilateral lower extremity strength with dorsiflexion. The patient had normal sensation bilaterally in upper and lower extremities. However, the patient had 3/5 lower bilateral extremity strength with hip flexion. Furthermore, that patient had bilateral absent Patellar and Achilles tendon reflexes. On further assessment, the patient's labs were unremarkable. A computed tomography scan of the brain was performed, which revealed no evidence of acute intracranial abnormalities. The report did endorse microvascular ischemic disease involving the white matter. These results were found to be secondary to aging. Magnetic resonance imaging scan of the brain and lumbar spinal cord was only positive for degenerative antegrade spondylolisthesis deformity at L5-S1. Over the next 24 hours, the patient reported worsening lower extremity paresthesias and weakness. The patient could no longer stand without assistance. The patient also stated that having neuropathic pain in bilateral lower extremities; burning, tingling, and electrical shock sensations. Furthermore, the patient described new difficulties with swallowing. An endoscopy was performed, and the patient was described to have esophageal dysmotility because the patient was unable to pass the barium pill during the examination. Consequently, a lumbar puncture was performed due to concern for disease progression. Lumbar cerebral spinal fluid studies revealed an elevated protein level (61 mg/dL), a normal white blood cell count (0 CUMM), and a cytoalbuminogenic dissociation. These results indicated acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (GBS). Neurologic consultation was obtained. No electrodiagnostic studies were performed. The patient was diagnosed with Guillen Barre Syndrome likely secondary to Shingrix vaccine. Treatment with intravenous immunoglobulin (2 g/kg divided over five days) was initiated. The patient showed gradual improvements with five days of treatment and was transferred to an acute rehabilitation facility (Hospital day 5). At discharge, the patient's bilateral Patellar and Achilles tendon reflexes remained absent. However, the patient was able to stand and ambulate with a walker. Five days after discharge to the rehab facility, the patient reported worsening of bilateral lower extremity pain (per patient, this pain was worse than her prior admission). The patient was therefore readmitted to the hospital. On examination, the patient had 5/5 bilateral upper extremity strength, 5/5 bilateral strength on lower extremity dorsiflexion, normal bilateral sensation in upper and lower extremities, and 3/5 bilateral lower extremity hip flexion strength. This strength assessment was consistent with the patient's previous presentation. Furthermore, light touch sensation was intact in all four extremities. There was no apparent sensory loss. Bilateral Achilles and Patellar tendon reflexes remained absent. However, the patient could no longer stand with and without assistance and therefore could no longer ambulate. This presentation significantly deviated from her prior discharge appearance. Initially the patient described neuropathic pain and therefore, the patient was treated with Gabapentin and amitriptyline. However, the patient became hyponatremic (133 mmol/L on admission to 122 mmol/L after treatment) and had significant fluctuations in her blood pressure (ranging from 110/67 mmHg to 182/88 mmHg). Additionally, the patient unfortunately feels due to weakness while attempting to walk with assistance. The patient suffered a nondisplaced spiral fracture through the distal fibular metaphysis and had a large ankle joint effusion. The patient was seen by Orthopedic Surgery and was placed in a CAM boot. Plasma exchange was initiated because the patient's muscular strength continued to decline, and her lower extremity pain was increasing. After undergoing three plasma exchange treatments, the patient showed remarkable improvement with lower extremity strength and power. The patient was then able to ambulate the hospital halls with the use of a walker and some assistance after five treatments of plasma exchange. Additionally, the patient's neuropathic pain improved. The patient was then discharged to an acute rehabilitation center with scheduled physical therapy. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.  The author commented, "We present a case of Guillian-Barre syndrome that occurred 10 days after Shingrix vaccine administration. We identified no other possible etiology of the patient's symptoms. The patient displayed several key features of GBS established by the Brighton Criteria of weakness; paresthesias, diminished Patellar and Achilles deep tendon reflexes, hyponatremia secondary to Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone secretion (SIADH), dysautonomia, and cytoalbuminological dissociation on cerebral spinal fluid analysis. We believe that this is an example of post-vaccine related Guillain-Barre Syndrome, given the timing of the presentation and when she received her vaccine. While electrodiagnostic studies have been used to help diagnose GBS secondary to bacterial, viral, and vaccination origins, these results are not necessary. The diagnosis of GBS is confirmed with the elevated CSF protein level and absence of deep tendon reflexes (found in 90% of GBS affected patients). Additionally, it can take up to four weeks before electrodiagnostic studies show loss of motor and sensory response secondary to GBS. There have been numerous vaccines connected to GBS, including the H1N1 swine flu vaccine and the pneumococcal vaccine. However, the newly release Shingrix vaccine has yet to be reported to be associated with this potentially life threatening polyradiculoneuropathy. Documented adverse reactions to the Shingrix vaccination from eight high quality randomized control trials, include local injection site rash or irritation, disseminated rash, herpes zoster infection in immunocompetent patients, and life-threatening complications in immunocompromised recipients. However, none of these studies demonstrated a relationship between Shingrix, nor the previous Zoster vaccine, to GBS. As a result, GBS likely secondary to the Shingrix vaccine could not have been expected in this patient after receiving this immunization. In summary, the bacterial lipopolysaccharide epitope acts as a molecular mimicker. The precise nature by which this occurs is still unclear. Therefore, the mechanism by which GBS may result from Shingrix vaccine remains unknown. If further cases reveal a similar association, this should be further explored. Per this case report and prior documentation of GBS secondary to herpes zoster, there is now evidence to state that antibodies generated in a lab against herpes zoster and then given intramuscularly via vaccination (Shingrix) may be a sufficient nidus for Guillain-Barre syndrome." The author concluded, "In summary, we present a case of GBS that occurred shortly after Shingrix vaccination. Our case is consistent with other vaccine and herpes zoster related cases of GBS. Clinicians should be cognizant of the possible association between Guillain-Barre syndrome and the new Shingrix vaccine." SYMPTOM_TEXT: Guillain-Barre syndrome; demyelinating polyneuropathy; tingling and numbness in his feet; numbness in his feet/PINPRICK SENSATION DIMINISHED; areflexia at biceps, brachioradialis, patella, and Achilles despite Jendrassik maneuver; diminished vibration bilaterally from the toes to the knees; weakness with foot dorsiflexion; Fall; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of guillain barre syndrome in a 79-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.  Concurrent medical conditions included neuropathy.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix. On an unknown date, 10 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced guillain barre syndrome (serious criteria GSK medically significant), demyelinating polyneuropathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant), tingling of extremity, hypoesthesia, areflexia, loss of sensation, joint range of motion decreased and fall. The patient was treated with doxycycline and immunoglobulins nos (Ivig). On an unknown date, the outcome of the guillain barre syndrome, demyelinating polyneuropathy, tingling of extremity, hypoesthesia, areflexia, loss of sensation, joint range of motion decreased and fall were unknown.   The reporter considered the guillain barre syndrome, demyelinating polyneuropathy, tingling of extremity, hypoesthesia, areflexia, loss of sensation, joint range of motion decreased and fall to be possibly related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS), in a 79-year-old male patient, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis.  The patient had a history of clinically diagnosed neuropathy by his primary care physician (PCP). No information on patient family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported. n an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with Shingrix (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported but it could be between 78 or 79 years old at the time of vaccination. On an unspecified date, 10 days after vaccination, the patient had onset of symptoms. The patient initially presented with symptoms of progressive tingling and numbness in his feet for over a week to the urgent care clinic. At the baseline, the patient was very active, and the history was negative for any other relevant symptoms. The neurological examination at the urgent care was reported unremarkable (no further details available). Due to the patient's history of outdoor activities, the patient got empirically treated with doxycycline, and blood drawn for tick-borne serologies came back negative. The patient returned with worsening paresthesia and weakness in his legs, which culminated in a fall. A neurological examination done on this visit showed diminished pinprick and vibration bilaterally from the toes to the knees with areflexia at biceps, brachioradialis, patella, and Achilles despite Jendrassik maneuver. Romberg was positive, with no dysmetria on finger to nose test. The patient gait was broad-based. There was no loss of sensation in the upper limbs. Motor examination showed a weakness with foot dorsiflexion and medical research council- MRC grading of 4/5 for bilateral hip flexion and knee extension. Lumbar puncture showed elevated cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) Protein: 195 mg/dl, with a normal corrected white blood cell (WBC) count. Electrodiagnostic study (Nerve conduction study (NCS)) revealed demyelinating polyneuropathy was done. The motor NCS shows prolonged latency and slowed conduction velocity in addition to reduced compound muscle action potential amplitudes in some nerves due to pre-existing neuropathy. The results of NCS were: Left median: nerve site was wrist showing latency 7.7 m/s (reference: less than 4.2 m/s) and compound muscle action potential (CMAP) amplitude was 4.0 mV (reference: more than 4.0 mV). Nerve site was elbow showing latency 14.3 m/s, CMAP amplitude was 3.6 mV and conduction velocity was 37.5 m/s (reference: 50 m/s). Right Ulnar: nerve site was wrist showing latency 4.2 m/s (reference: less than 3.6 m/s) and CMAP amplitude was 7.2 mV (reference: more than 5.0 mV). Nerve site was below elbow showing latency 10.3 m/s, CMAP amplitude was 6.0 mV and conduction velocity was 41.3 m/s. Nerve site was above elbow showing latency 13.0 m/s, CMAP amplitude 5.7 mV and conduction velocity was 36.6 m/s (reference: 50.0 m/s). Left/Right Peroneal: nerve site was ankle and results were not recordable for both left and right (reference for latency less than 6.0 m/s; reference for CMPA amplitude more than 2.5 mV). Left tibial: nerve site was ankle showing latency 15.6 m/s (reference: less than 6.6 m/s) and CMAP amplitude was 0.9 mV (reference: more than 2.0 mV). Nerve site was knee showing latency 32.2 m/s, CMAP amplitude was 0.3 mV and conduction velocity was 27.1 m/s. Right tibial: nerve site was wrist showing latency 9.1 m/s (reference: less than 6.6 m/s) and CMAP amplitude was 1.9 mV (reference: more than 2.0 mV). Nerve site was knee showing latency 27.1 m/s, CMAP amplitude was 1.1 mV and conduction velocity was 25.2 m/s (reference: 40 m/s). Left Peroneal Tibialis Anterior: nerve site was fibular head showing latency 4.0 m/s (reference: less than 4.0 m/s) and CMAP amplitude was 4.0 mV (reference: more than 4.0 mV). Nerve site was knee showing latency 6.9 m/s, CMAP amplitude was 3.9 mV and conduction velocity was 33.7 m/s (reference: 40 m/s). Right Peroneal Tibialis Anterior: nerve site was fibular head showing latency 12.4 m/s (reference: less than 4.0 m/s) and CMAP amplitude was 2.5 mV (reference: more than 4.0 mV). Nerve site was knee showing latency 14.4 m/s, CMAP amplitude was 2.2 mV and conduction velocity was 48.3 m/s (reference: 40 m/s). Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the lumbar spine with contrast showed enlarged and enhancing nerve roots involving L1 through S1. The patient was diagnosed with GBS. The patient was started on intravenous immunoglobulins (IVIg) (2g/kg body weight over 5 days), resulting in improvement of strength with residual pinprick sensation deficit only in the toes and reduced vibration in his feet from his previous neuropathy two months after treatment. Outcome was not reported. The authors commented, The temporal association of the development of autoimmune neuromuscular disorders and vaccine administration is well documented. Several vaccines, although beneficial, have proposed to be implicated in the development of autoimmune disorders, especially GBS. The precise mechanism is unknown, but one probable cause could be the vaccine components eliciting an exaggerated immune response. As stated earlier, the Shingrix vaccine consists of the glycoprotein E and adjuvant AS01B. Adjuvants, by definition, are substances that augment antigen-specific immune response. However, studies reported the role of adjuvants in causing autoimmunity by molecular mimicry and simulating an immune reaction in animal models or humans similar to the bacterial or viral infections. Although hypothesized that the Shingrix vaccine may have led to GBS in our patient, the exact pathogenesis is still not clear. In addition to the adjuvants, immune responses directed against the Glycoprotein E can also result in autoantibodies or T-cell activation that cross-react with ganglioside GM1 in the myelin resulting in immunological damage to the peripheral nerve sheaths. Further in vitro studies will be required to assess this relationship.   Following review below correction was done for the date received on 3rd December 2020: The patient country was updated.
